# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: siege-hook
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:siege-hook/alb-limes] The **Alb Limes** (German: *Alblimes*) is a Roman frontier fortification or *limes* of the late 1st century AD in the Swabian Jura, also known as the Swabian Alb.
[src:siege-hook/alb-limes] The Alb Limes runs for just under 135 kilometres from Rottweil (Latin: *Arae Flaviae*) in the southwest to Heidenheim an der Brenz (Latin: *Aquileia*), Germany, in the northeast.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] It was named after Ambracia, who according to some myths was Augeas daughter, while others describe her as Apollo's granddaughter and the daughter of Melaneus, king of the Dryope.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] According to a different story, the town was named after Ambrax, Thesprotus son and Lycaon's grandson.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] Ambracia was founded between 650 and 625 BC by Gorgus, son of the Corinthian tyrant Cypselus, at which time its economy was based on farmlands, fishing, timber for shipbuilding, and the exportation of the produce of Epirus.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] After the expulsion of Gorgus's son Periander its government developed into a strong democracy.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] Ambraciot politics featured many frontier disputes with the Amphilochians and Acarnanians.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] Hence it took a prominent part in the Peloponnesian War until the crushing defeat at Idomene (426), which crippled its resources.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] In the 4th century BC, it continued its traditional policy but in 338 was besieged by Philip II of Macedon.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] With the assistance of Corinth and Athens, it escaped complete domination at Philip's hands but was nevertheless forced to accept a Macedonian garrison.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] In 294 BC, after forty-three years of semi-autonomy under Macedonian suzerainty, Ambracia was given by the son of Cassander to Pyrrhus, king of Epirus, who made it his capital and adorned it with palaces, temples, and theatres.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] In the wars of Philip V of Macedon and the Epirotes against the Aetolian League (220–205), Ambracia passed from one alliance to the other but ultimately joined the latter confederacy.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] During the struggle of the Aetolians against Rome, it withstood a stubborn siege, including the first known use of poison gas against the Romans' siege tunnels.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] There was an ancient book, titled *Ambrakika* (Ἀμβρακικά), by the writer Athanadas, that detailed the history of Ambracia.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] No copies of the work survive, but it was referred to by later writers such as Antoninus Liberalis as an authority on the subject.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] Ambracia was captured and plundered by Marcus Fulvius Nobilior in 189 BC, after which it was declared by Rome a "free city" and gradually fell into insignificance.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] The foundation by Augustus of Nicopolis, into which the remaining inhabitants were drafted, left the site desolate.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] In Byzantine times a new settlement took its place under the name of Arta.
[src:siege-hook/ambracia] Some fragmentary walls of large, well-dressed blocks near this latter town indicate the early prosperity of Ambracia.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] Originally some 56 km (35 mi) long, it stretches from Evcik İskelesi in Çatalca at the Black Sea coast across the Thracian peninsula to the coast of the Sea of Marmara at 6 km (3.7 mi) west of Silivri (ancient Selymbria).
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] It ran from north to south through the locations what are today Karacaköy, Gümüşpınar, Pınarca, Kurfallı, Fener, Alipaşa Neighborhood and Silivri Altınorak.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] Remains of the wall are visible in Gümüşpınar junction in Karacaköy, Hisartepe in Yalıköy, Pınarca in İhsaniye and Kurfallı village.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] The wall was part of an additional outer defense system for Constantinople, capital of the Eastern Roman Empire and probably continued in use until the 7th century.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] The wall was named after the Emperor Anastasius I (r.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] However, there is evidence that the fortification already existed in 469 during the reign of Leo I (r.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] 476–491), and it was maintained and renewed by Anastasius in the time from 507 to 512.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] The wall had a thickness of 3.3 m (11 ft) and a height over 5 m (16 ft).
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] It was built complete with towers, gates, forts, ditches and a military way to protect Constantinople from invasions from the west by Huns, Slavs and Bulgars.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] A rectangular *castrum* with dimensions of 250 m (820 ft) by 300 m (980 ft) existed also in the central section of the wall.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] The wall fell into ruin after it was abandoned in the 7th century because of the difficulty of keeping it manned and repaired.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] Over the centuries, the stone of more than half of the total length was reused in other local buildings.
[src:siege-hook/anastasian-wall] It is best preserved in the woodlands of the northern sector.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Defensive walls are a feature of ancient Roman architecture.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Romans generally fortified cities, rather than building stand-alone fortresses, but there are some fortified camps, such as the Saxon Shore forts like Porchester Castle in England.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] City walls were already significant in Etruscan architecture, and in the struggle for control of Italy under the early Republic many more were built, using different techniques.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] These included tightly fitting massive irregular polygonal blocks, shaped to fit exactly in a way reminiscent of later Inca work.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Romans called a simple rampart wall an agger; at this date great height was not necessary.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Servian Wall around Rome was an ambitious project of the early 4th century BC.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The wall was up to 10 metres (32.8 ft) in height in places, 3.6 metres (12 ft) wide at its base, 11 km (7 mi) long, and is believed to have had 16 main gates, though many of these are mentioned only from writings, with no other known remains.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Some of it had a *fossa* or ditch in front, and an agger behind, and it was enough to deter Hannibal.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Later the Aurelian Wall replaced it, enclosing an expanded city, and using more sophisticated designs, with small forts at intervals.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] The Romans walled major cities and towns in areas they saw as vulnerable, and parts of many walls remain incorporated in later defences, as at Córdoba (2nd century BC), Chester (earth and wood in the 70s AD, stone from c.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Strategic walls defending the frontiers of the Empire by running across open country were far rarer, and Hadrian's Wall (from 122) and the Antonine Wall (from 142, abandoned only 8 years after completion) are the most significant examples, both on the Pictish frontier.
[src:siege-hook/ancient-roman-defensive-walls] Most defences of the borders of the Roman Empire relied on systems of forts and roads without attempting a continuous barrier.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The **Antonine Wall** (Latin: *Vallum Antonini*) was a turf fortification on stone foundations, built by the Romans across what is now the Central Belt of Scotland, between the Firth of Clyde and the Firth of Forth.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Built some twenty years after Hadrian's Wall to the south, and intended to supersede it, while it was garrisoned it was the northernmost frontier barrier of the Roman Empire.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It spanned approximately 63 kilometres (39 miles) and was about 3 metres (10 feet) high and 5 metres (16 feet) wide.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Lidar scans have been carried out to establish the length of the wall and the Roman distance units used.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Security was bolstered by a deep ditch on the northern side.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It is thought that there was a wooden palisade on top of the turf.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The barrier was the second of two "great walls" created by the Romans in Great Britain in the second century AD.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Its ruins are less evident than those of the better-known and longer Hadrian's Wall to the south, primarily because the turf and wood wall has largely weathered away, unlike its stone-built southern predecessor.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Construction began in AD 142 at the order of Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Estimates of how long it took to complete vary widely, with six and twelve years most commonly proposed.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Antoninus Pius never visited Britain, unlike his predecessor Hadrian.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Pressure from the Caledonians probably led Antoninus to send the empire's troops farther north.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was protected by 16 forts with small fortlets between them; troop movement was facilitated by a road linking all the sites known as the Military Way.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The soldiers who built the wall commemorated the construction and their struggles with the Caledonians with decorative slabs, twenty of which survive.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned only eight years after completion, and the garrisons relocated rearward to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Most of the wall and its associated fortifications have been destroyed over time, but some remains are visible.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Many of these have come under the care of Historic Environment Scotland and the UNESCO World Heritage Committee.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Roman Emperor Antoninus Pius ordered the construction of the Antonine Wall around 142.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Quintus Lollius Urbicus, governor of Roman Britain at the time, initially supervised the effort, which may have taken as long as twelve years.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The wall stretches 63 kilometres (39 miles) from Old Kilpatrick in West Dunbartonshire on the Firth of Clyde to Carriden near Bo'ness on the Firth of Forth.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The wall was intended to extend Roman territory and dominance by replacing Hadrian's Wall 160 kilometres (100 miles) to the south, as the frontier of *Britannia*.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] But while the Romans did establish forts and temporary camps further north of the Antonine Wall in order to protect their routes to northern Britain, they did not conquer the Caledonians, and the Antonine Wall suffered many attacks.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Romans called the land north of the wall *Caledonia*, though in some contexts the term may refer to the whole area north of Hadrian's Wall.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The land north of the Antonine Wall became known as Albany after the settlement of the Gaels in the 6th century.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was shorter than Hadrian's Wall and built of turf on a stone foundation, but it was still an impressive achievement.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It was also a simpler fortification than Hadrian's Wall insofar as it did not have a subsidiary ditch system (Vallum) behind it to the south.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] As built, the wall was typically a bank, about three metres (10 feet) high, made of layered turves and occasionally earth with a wide ditch on the north side, and a military way on the south.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The stone foundations and wing walls of the original forts on the Antonine Wall demonstrate that the original plan was to build a stone wall similar to Hadrian's Wall, but this was quickly amended.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Romans initially planned to build forts every 10 kilometres (6 miles), but this was soon revised to every 3.3 kilometres (2 miles), resulting in a total of nineteen forts along the wall.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The best preserved but also one of the smallest forts is Rough Castle Fort.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] In addition to the forts, there are at least nine smaller fortlets, very likely on Roman mile spacings, which formed part of the original scheme, some of which were later replaced by forts.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The most visible fortlet is Kinneil, at the eastern end of the Wall, near Bo'ness.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] There was once a remarkable Roman structure within sight of the Antonine Wall at Stenhousemuir, which took its name from the Roman "stone house".
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] This was Arthur's O'on, a circular stone domed monument or rotunda, which might have been a temple, or a *tropaeum*, a victory monument.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It was demolished for its stone in 1743, though a replica exists at Penicuik House.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] In addition to the line of the Wall itself there are a number of coastal forts both in the East (e.g.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Inveresk) and West (Outerwards and Lurg Moor), which should be considered as outposts and/or supply bases to the Wall itself.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] In addition a number of forts further north were brought back into service in the Gask Ridge area, including Ardoch, Strageath, Bertha (Perth) and probably Dalginross and Cargill.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Recent research by Glasgow University has shown that the distance stones, stone sculptures unique to the Antonine Wall which were embedded in the wall to mark the lengths built by each legion, were brightly painted unlike their present bare appearance.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] These stones are preserved in the university's museum and are said to be the best-preserved examples of statuary from any Roman frontier.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Several of the slabs have been analysed by various techniques including portable X-ray fluorescence (pXRF).
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Tiny remnants of paint have been detected by surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS).
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Several of the distance slabs have been scanned and 3-D videos produced.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] There are plans to reproduce the slabs, both digitally and in real physical copies, with their authentic colours.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] A copy of the Bridgeness Slab has already been made and can be found in Bo'ness.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It is also expected that lottery funding will allow replicas of distance markers to be placed along the length of the wall.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The wall was abandoned within two decades of completion when the Roman legions withdrew to Hadrian's Wall in 162, and over time may have reached an accommodation with the Brythonic tribes of the area, whom they may have fostered as possible buffer states which would later become "The Old North".
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] After a series of attacks in 197, the emperor Septimius Severus arrived in Scotland in 208, and campaigned against the Maeatae (based in the central Midland Valley on either side of the Firth of Clyde – Firth of Forth line) and the Caledonians to their north.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] While he carried out substantial work on Hadrian's Wall at the time, there is no evidence of any attention being paid to the remains of the Antonine Wall during the campaigns of 208–210.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] References in Late Roman sources to Severus' wall-building activities led to later scholars like Bede mistaking references to the Antonine Wall for ones to Hadrian's Wall.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] In the centuries that the Antonine Wall has lain abandoned, it has influenced culture between the Forth and the Clyde.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Bede associated Gildas's turf wall with the Antonine Wall.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Bede obviously identified Gildas's stone wall as Hadrian's Wall, but he sets its construction in the 5th century rather than the 120s, and does not mention Hadrian.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] And he would appear to have believed that the ditch-and-mound barrier known as the Vallum (just to the south of, and contemporary with, Hadrian's Wall) was the rampart constructed by Severus.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Many centuries would pass before just who built what became apparent.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] In medieval histories, such as the chronicles of John of Fordun, the wall is called *Gryme's dyke*.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Fordun says that the name came from the grandfather of the imaginary king Eugenius son of Farquahar.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] This evolved over time into Graham's dyke – a name still found in Bo'ness at the wall's eastern end – and then linked with Clan Graham.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Of note is that Graeme in some parts of Scotland is a nickname for the devil, and Gryme's Dyke would thus be the Devil's Dyke, mirroring the name of the Roman limes in Southern Germany often called 'Teufelsmauer'.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Grímr and Grim are bynames for Odin or Wodan, who might be credited with the wish to build earthworks in unreasonably short periods of time.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] This name is the same one found as Grim's Ditch several times in England in connection with early ramparts: for example, near Wallingford, Oxfordshire or between Berkhamsted (Herts) and Bradenham (Bucks).
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Other names used by antiquarians include the Wall of Pius and the Antonine Vallum, after Antoninus Pius.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Edmund Spenser in Book II of *The Faerie Queene* (1590) alludes to the Wall, misattributing it to Constantine II.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Hector Boece in his 1527 *History of Scotland* called it the "wall of Abercorn", repeating the story that it had been destroyed by Graham.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Renaissance patrons in the 16th century, including George Keith, 5th Earl Marischal, who were exposed to the world of international scholarship through diplomacy, began to collect antiquities.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Earl Marischal set a stone from the Antonine Wall in the walls of Dunnotar Castle and had it painted and gilded, probably by Andrew Melville of Stonehaven.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The stone is now at the Hunterian Museum in Glasgow and residual paint traces probably remaining from its later reuse have been analysed.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The UK government's nomination of the Antonine Wall for World Heritage status to the international conservation body UNESCO was first officially announced in 2003.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It has been backed by the Scottish Government since 2005 and by Scotland's then Culture Minister Patricia Ferguson since 2006.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] It became the UK's official nomination in late January 2007, and MSPs were called to support the bid anew in May 2007.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Antonine Wall was listed as an extension to the World Heritage Site "Frontiers of the Roman Empire" on 7 July 2008.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Though the Antonine Wall is mentioned in the text, it does not appear on UNESCO's map of world heritage properties.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Several individual sites along the line of the wall are in the care of Historic Environment Scotland.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] All sites are unmanned and open at all reasonable times.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The first capable effort to systematically map the Antonine Wall was undertaken in 1764 by William Roy, the forerunner of the Ordnance Survey.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] He provided accurate and detailed drawings of its remains, and where the wall has been destroyed by later development, his maps and drawings are now the only reliable record of it.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] In the 19th century, the Ordnance Survey showed the visible traces of the wall in some detail on its first- and second-edition maps at 25-inch and 6-inch scales, but no attempt was made then to undertake archaeological work.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Sir George Macdonald carried out systematic work on the wall that was published in 1911 and in an expanded second edition in 1934.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] His work provided the basis for a large-scale (25-inch) folio produced by the Ordnance Survey in 1931.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] The Ordnance Survey produced a revised folio in 1954–1957, and then carried out a new complete survey in 1979–80.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] They also published a smaller-scale map of the Wall, at 1:25,000 in 1969.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Further mapping activity was carried out to support the nomination of the Wall as a World Heritage Site.
[src:siege-hook/antonine-wall] Modern computer techniques like using GIS and LIDAR can now map the wall in three dimensions, making it much easier to study, for example, how visible forts and fortlets were to those at their neighbouring stations along the wall.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The ***auxilia*** (Classical Latin: [au̯kˈsɪli.a], lit.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 'auxiliaries') were introduced as non-citizen troops attached to the citizen legions by Augustus after his reorganisation of the Imperial Roman army from 27 BC.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the 2nd century, the *Auxilia* contained the same number of infantry as the legions and, in addition, provided almost all of the Roman army's cavalry (especially light cavalry and archers) and more specialised troops.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The *auxilia* thus represented three-fifths of Rome's regular land forces at that time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Like their legionary counterparts, auxiliary recruits were mostly volunteers, not conscripts.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The *Auxilia* were mainly recruited from the *peregrini*, free provincial subjects who did not hold Roman citizenship and constituted the vast majority of the population in the 1st and 2nd centuries (c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In contrast to the legions, which only admitted Roman citizens, members of the *Auxilia* could be recruited from territories outside of Roman control.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Reliance on the various contingents of non-Italic troops, especially cavalry, increased when the Roman Republic employed them in increasing numbers to support its legions after 200 BC.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Julio-Claudian period (27 BC–68 AD) saw the transformation of the *Auxilia* from motley levies to a standing corps with standardised structure, equipment and conditions of service.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the end of the period, there were no significant differences between legionaries and auxiliaries in terms of training and combat capability.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Auxiliary regiments were often stationed in provinces other than that in which they were originally raised, for reasons of security and to foster the process of Romanization in the provinces.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The regimental names of many auxiliary units persisted into the 4th century, but by then the units in question were different in size, structure, and quality from their predecessors.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The mainstay of the Roman republic's war machine was the manipular legion, a heavy infantry unit suitable for close-quarter engagements on more or less any terrain, which was probably adopted sometime during the Samnite Wars (343–290 BC).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Despite its formidable strength, the legion had a number of deficiencies, especially a lack of cavalry.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Around 200 BC, a legion of 4,200 infantry had a cavalry arm of only 300 horse (just 7% of the total force).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This was because the class of citizens who could afford to pay for their own horse and equipment – the equestrian order, the second rank in Roman society, after the senatorial order – was relatively small.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In addition, the legion lacked missile forces such as slingers and archers.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Until 200 BC, the bulk of a Roman army's cavalry was provided by Rome's regular Italian allies (*socii*), commonly known as the "Latin" allies, which made up the Roman military confederation.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This was Rome's defence system until the Social War of 91–88 BC.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Italian forces were organised into *alae* (literally 'wings', because they were generally posted on the flanks of the Roman line of battle).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] An allied *ala*, commanded by three Roman *praefecti sociorum*, was similar or slightly larger in infantry size (4–5,000 men) to a legion, but contained a more substantial cavalry contingent: 900 horse, three times the legionary contingent.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Since a pre-Social War consular army always contained an equal number of legions and *alae*, 75% of its cavalry was provided by the Latin allies.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Roman/Latin cavalry was sufficient while Rome was in conflict with other states in the mountainous Italian peninsula, which also disposed of limited cavalry resources.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But, as Rome was confronted by external enemies that deployed far more powerful cavalry elements, such as the Gauls and the Carthaginians, the Roman deficiency in cavalry numbers could be a serious liability, which in the Second Punic War (218–202 BC) resulted in crushing defeats.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Hannibal's major victories at the Trebia and at Cannae, were owed to his Spanish and Gallic heavy cavalry, which far outnumbered the Roman and Latin levies, and to his Numidians, light, fast cavalry which the Romans wholly lacked.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The decisive Roman victory at Zama in 202 BC, which ended the war, owed much to the Numidian cavalry provided by king Massinissa, which outnumbered the Roman/Latin cavalry fielded by two to one.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] From then, Roman armies were always accompanied by large numbers of non-Italian cavalry: Numidian light cavalry and, later, Gallic heavy cavalry.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] For example, Caesar relied heavily on Gallic and German cavalry for his Conquest of Gaul (58–51 BC).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] As the role of native cavalry grew, that of Roman/Latin cavalry diminished.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the early 1st century BC, Roman cavalry was phased out altogether.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] After the Social War, the *socii* were all granted Roman citizenship, the Latin **alae** abolished, and the **socii** recruited into the legions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Furthermore, Roman equestrians were no longer required to perform cavalry service after this time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The late Republican legion was thus probably bereft of cavalry (a tiny cavalry force of 120 men was probably added back to the legion under Augustus).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the outbreak of the Second Punic War, the Romans were remedying the legions' other deficiencies by using non-Italian specialised troops.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Livy reports Hiero of Syracuse offering to supply Rome with archers and slingers in 217 BC.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] From 200 BC onwards, specialist troops were hired as mercenaries on a regular basis: *sagittarii* (archers) from Crete, and *funditores* (slingers) from the Balearic Isles almost always accompanied Roman legions in campaigns all over the Mediterranean.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The other main sources of non-Italian troops in the late Republic were subject provincials, allied cities and Rome's *amici* (satellite kings).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] During the late Republic, non-Italian units were led by their own native chiefs, and their internal organisation was left to their own commanders.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The units varied widely in dress, equipment, and weapons.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] They were normally raised for specific campaigns and often disbanded soon afterwards, in a similar manner to the earlier **socii** militia legions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] It appears that not all indigenous units were disbanded at the end of the civil war period (31 BC).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Some of the more experienced units were kept in existence to complement the legions, and became the core of the standing auxiliary forces that developed in the Julio-Claudian period.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] During the early part of Augustus' rule (27 BC onwards), the corps of regular Auxilia was created.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] It was clearly inspired by the Latin forces of the pre-Social War Republic, as a corps of non-citizen troops parallel to the legions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But there were fundamental differences, the same as between Republican and Augustan legions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Latin forces of the Republic were made up of part-time conscripts in units that would be raised and disbanded for and after particular campaigns.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Augustan Auxilia were mainly volunteer professionals serving in permanent units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The unit structure of the Auxilia also differed from the Latin **alae**, which were like legions with a larger cavalry arm.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] However, Augustus organised the Auxilia into regiments the size of cohorts (a tenth the size of legions), due to the much greater flexibility of the smaller unit size.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Further, the regiments were of three types: *ala* (cavalry), *cohors (peditata)* (infantry) and *cohors equitata* (mixed cavalry/infantry).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The evidence for the size of the Augustus' new units is not clear-cut, with our most precise evidence dating to the 2nd century, by which time the unit strengths may have changed.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] *Cohortes* were likely modelled on legionary cohorts i.e. six *centuriae* of about 80 men each (total about 480 men).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] **Alae** were divided into *turmae* (squadrons) of 30 (or 32) men, each under a *decurio* (literally: 'leader of ten').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This title derives from the old Roman cavalry of the pre-Social War republic, in which each *turma* was under the command of three *decuriones*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] *Cohortes equitatae* were infantry *cohortes* with a cavalry contingent of four *turmae* attached.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By 19 BC, the Cantabrian and Asturian Wars were concluded, leading to the annexation of northern Hispania and Lusitania.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Judging by the names of attested auxiliary regiments, these parts of the Iberian peninsula soon became a major source of recruits.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Then the Danubian regions were annexed: Raetia (annexed 15 BC), Noricum (16 BC), Pannonia (9 BC) and Moesia (6 AD), becoming, with Illyricum, the Principate's most important source of auxiliary recruits for its entire duration.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the East, where the Syrians already provided the bulk of the Roman army's archers, Augustus annexed Galatia (25 BC) and Judaea: the former, a region in central Anatolia with a Celtic-speaking people, became an important source of recruits.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Africa, Egypt, Cyrene, and Numidia (25 BC) were added to the empire.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Numidia (modern day Eastern Algeria) was home to the Numidians/Moors, the ancestors of today's Berber people.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Their light cavalry (*equites Maurorum*) was highly prized and had alternately fought and assisted the Romans for well over two centuries: they now started to be recruited into the regular Auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Even more Mauri units were formed after the annexation of Mauretania (NW Algeria, Morocco), the rest of the Berber homeland, in 44 AD by emperor Claudius (ruled 41–54).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Recruitment was thus heavy throughout the Augustan period, with a steady increase in the number of units formed.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By AD 23, the Roman historian Tacitus records that there were roughly the same numbers of auxiliaries in service as there were legionaries.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Since at this time there were 25 legions of c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 5,000 men each, the Auxilia thus amounted to c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] During the early Julio-Claudian period, many auxiliary regiments raised in frontier provinces were stationed in or near their home provinces, except during periods of major crises such as the Cantabrian Wars, when they were deployed temporarily in theatre.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This carried the obvious risk if their own tribe or ethnic group rebelled against Rome (or attacked the Roman frontier from outside the Empire), auxiliary troops could be tempted to make common cause with them.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Romans would then be faced by an enemy that included units fully equipped and trained by themselves, thus losing their usual tactical advantages over tribal foes.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] (This strategy was never revived by later emperors).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] At a collective level, the risk was even greater, as the hugely dangerous Illyrian revolt proved.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The central Illyrian tribes were tough and spartan shepherds of the Bosnian mountains and excellent soldier material.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Their territory formed part of the strategic province of Illyricum, recently expanded to include the territory of the Pannonii, Celticised Illyrian tribes based on the west bank of the Danube who were subjugated by Rome in 12–9 BC (the *Bellum Pannonicum*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the start of the Common Era, they were an important recruitment base for the auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But discontent was festering among the Illyrian tribes, largely due to what they saw as the rapacity of Roman tax officials.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In AD 6, several regiments of Dalmatae, a warlike Illyrian tribe, were ordered to report to a designated location to prepare to join Augustus' stepson and senior military commander Tiberius in a war against the Germans.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Instead, they mutinied at the assembly point, and defeated a Roman force sent against them.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Dalmatae were soon joined by the Breuci, another Illyrian tribe that supplied several auxiliary regiments.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] They gave battle to a second Roman force from Moesia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] They lost, but inflicted heavy casualties.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The rebels were now joined by a large number of other Illyrian tribes.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Dalmatae attacked the port of Salona and overran the Adriatic coast, defeating a Roman force and exposing the Roman heartland of Italy to the fear of a rebel invasion.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Augustus ordered Tiberius to break off operations in Germany and move his main army to Illyricum.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Romans had now deployed no less than 15 legions and an equivalent number of auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 150,000 men, including at least 50 auxiliary cohorts composed, exceptionally, of Roman citizens.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] These special units were accorded the title *civium Romanorum* ('of Roman citizens'), or *c.R.* for short.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] After the Illyrian revolt, these cohorts remained in being and recruited non-citizens like other auxiliary units, but retained their prestigious *c.R.* title.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In addition, the regular forces were assisted by a large number of allied troops from neighbouring Thrace deployed by their king Rhoemetalces I, a Roman *amicus* (puppet king).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Romans faced further reverses on the battlefield and a savage guerrilla war in the Bosnian mountains.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] It took them three years of hard fighting to quell the revolt, which was described by the Roman historian Suetonius, writing in c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] AD 100, as the most difficult conflict faced by Rome since the Punic Wars over two centuries earlier.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Tiberius finally succeeded in quelling the revolt in 9 AD.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This was apparently lucky timing for the Romans: that same year Arminius destroyed Varus' three legions in Germany.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Roman high command had no doubt that Arminius would have formed a grand alliance with the Illyrians.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Despite the gravity of this rebellion, the Illyrians went on, alongside their neighbours the Thracians, to become the backbone of the Roman army.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the 2nd century, with roughly half the Roman army deployed on the Danube frontier, the auxilia and legions alike were dominated by Illyrian recruits.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the 3rd century, Illyrians largely replaced Italians in the senior officer echelons of *praefecti* of auxiliary regiments and *tribuni militum* of legions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Finally, from AD 268 to 379, virtually all emperors, including Diocletian and Constantine the Great, were Romanised Illyrians from the provinces of Dalmatia, Moesia Superior and Pannonia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] These were members of a military aristocracy, outstanding soldiers who saved the empire from collapse in the turbulent late 3rd century.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Significant development of the Auxilia appears to have taken place during the rule of the emperor Claudius (41–54 AD).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] A minimum term of service of 25 years was established, at the end of which the retiring auxiliary soldier, and all his children, were awarded Roman citizenship.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This is deduced from the fact that the first known Roman military diplomas date from the time of Claudius.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This was a folding bronze tablet engraved with the details of the soldier's service record, which he could use to prove his citizenship.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Claudius also decreed that prefects of auxiliary regiments must all be of equestrian rank, thus excluding centurions from such commands.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The fact that auxiliary commanders were now all of the same social rank as most *tribuni militum*, (military tribunes, a legion's senior staff officers, all of whom only one, the *tribunus laticlavius*, was of the higher senatorial rank), probably indicates that auxilia now enjoyed greater prestige.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Indigenous chiefs continued to command some auxiliary regiments, and were probably granted equestrian rank for the purpose.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] It is also likely that auxiliary pay was standardised at this time, but estimates exist only for the Julio-Claudian period.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Auxiliary uniform, armour, weapons and equipment were probably standardised by the end of the Julio-Claudian period.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Auxiliary equipment was broadly similar to that of the legions (see Section 2.1 below for possible differences in armour).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By 68 AD, there was little difference between most auxiliary infantry and their legionary counterparts in equipment, training and fighting capability.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The main difference was that auxilia contained combat cavalry, both heavy and light, and other specialized units that legions lacked.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Claudius annexed to the empire three regions that became important sources of auxiliary recruits: Britannia (43 AD), and the former client kingdoms of Mauretania (44) and Thracia (46).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The latter became as important as Illyria as a source of auxiliary recruits, especially cavalry and archers.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Britain in mid-2nd century contained the largest number of auxiliary regiments in any single province: about 60 out of about 400 (15%).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the rule of Nero (54–68), auxiliary numbers may have reached, by one estimate, about 200,000 men, implying about 400 regiments.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Batavi, a Germanic tribe, inhabited the region today known as Gelderland (Netherlands), in the Rhine river delta, then known as the *Insula Batavorum* ('Island of the Batavi', because it is surrounded by branches of the Rhine), part of the Roman province of Germania Inferior.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] They were a warlike people, skilled horsemen, boatmen and swimmers.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In return for the unusual privilege of exemption from *tributum* (direct taxes on land and heads normally exacted from *peregrini*), they supplied a disproportionate number of recruits to the Julio-Claudian auxilia: one **ala** and eight *cohortes*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] They also provided most of Augustus' elite personal bodyguard unit (the *Germani corpore custodes*), which continued in service until 68 AD.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Batavi auxilia amounted to about 5,000 men, implying that during the entire Julio-Claudian period, over 50% of all Batavi males reaching military age (16 years) may have enlisted in the auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Thus the Batavi, although just 0.05% of the total population of the empire of c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 70 million in 23 AD, supplied about 4% of the total auxilia i.e.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] They were regarded by the Romans as the very best (*fortissimi*, *validissimi*) of their auxiliary, and indeed all, their forces.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In Roman service, both their cavalry and infantry had perfected a technique for swimming across rivers wearing full armour and weapons.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 'Julius the Citizen', clearly a Latin name adopted on gaining Roman citizenship, not his native one) was a hereditary prince of the Batavi and the prefect of a Batavi cohort.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] A veteran of 25 years' service, he had distinguished himself by service in Britain, where he and the eight Batavi cohorts had played a crucial role in both the Roman invasion in 43 AD and the subsequent subjugation of southern Britain.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By 69, however, Civilis, the Batavi regiments and the Batavi people had become utterly disaffected with Rome.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] After the Batavi regiments were withdrawn from Britain to Italy in 66, Civilis and his brother (also a prefect) were arrested by the governor of Germania Inferior on a fabricated accusation of sedition.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The governor ordered his brother's execution, while Civilis, who as a Roman citizen had the right to appeal to the emperor, was sent to Rome in chains for judgement by Nero.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] He was released by Nero's overthrower and successor, Galba, but the latter also disbanded the imperial bodyguard unit for their loyalty to Nero.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This alienated several hundred crack Batavi troops, and indeed the whole Batavi nation who regarded it as a grave insult.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] At the same time, relations collapsed between the Batavi cohorts and the legion to which they had been attached since the invasion of Britain 25 years earlier (*XIV Gemina*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Their mutual hatred erupted in open fighting on at least two occasions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] At this juncture, the Roman empire was convulsed by its first major civil war since the Battle of Actium exactly a century earlier: the Year of the Four Emperors (69–70 AD).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The governor of Germania Inferior, ordered to raise more troops, outraged the Batavi by attempting to conscript more Batavi than the maximum stipulated in their treaty.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The brutality and corruption of the Roman recruiting-centurions (including incidents of sexual assault on Batavi young men) brought already deep discontent in the Batavi homeland to the boil.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Civilis now led his people in open revolt.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Initially, he claimed he was supporting the bid for power of Vespasian, the general in command of the legions in Syria, whom Civilis had probably befriended when both were involved in the Roman invasion of Britain 25 years earlier (Vespasian was then commander of the legion *II Augusta*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But the uprising soon became a bid for independence.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Civilis exploited the fact that some legions were absent from the Rhine area due to the civil war, and the rest under-strength.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In addition, the Roman commanders and their rank-and-file soldiers were divided by loyalty to rival emperors.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Civilis quickly won the support of the Batavi's neighbours and kinsmen, the Cananefates, who in turn won over the Frisii.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] First the rebel allies captured two Roman forts in their territory, and a cohort of Tungri defected to Civilis.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Then two legions sent against Civilis were defeated when their companion Batavi **ala** defected to his side.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The *Classis Germanica* (Rhine flotilla), largely manned by Batavi, was seized by Civilis.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Most importantly, the eight Batavi cohorts stationed at Mainz with *XIV Gemina* mutinied and joined him, defeating at Bonn a Roman force that attempted to block their return to their homeland.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By now, Civilis commanded at least 12 regiments (6,000 men) of Roman-trained and equipped auxiliary troops, as well as a much larger number of tribal levies.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] A number of German tribes from beyond the Rhine joined his cause.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Several other German and Gallic units sent against him deserted, as the revolt spread to the rest of Gallia Belgica, including the Tungri, Lingones and Treviri tribes.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] He was able to destroy the two remaining legions in Germania Inferior, (*V Alaudae* and *XV Primigenia*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By this stage, Rome's entire position on the Rhine and even in Gaul was imperiled.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Their civil war over, the Romans mustered a huge task force of eight legions (five dispatched from Italy, two from Spain and one from Britain) to deal with Civilis.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Its commander Petillius Cerialis had to fight two difficult battles, at Trier and Xanten, before he could overrun the Batavi's homeland.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Tacitus' surviving narrative breaks off as he describes a meeting on an island in the Rhine delta between Civilis and Cerialis to discuss peace terms.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] We do not know the outcome of this meeting or Civilis' ultimate fate.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But, in view of his former friendship with Vespasian, who had already offered him a pardon, and the fact that the Romans still needed the Batavi levies, it is likely that the terms were lenient by Roman standards.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Petilius Cerialis took a number of reconstituted Batavi units with him to Britain, and the Batavi regiments continued to serve with special distinction in Britain and elsewhere for the rest of the 1st century and beyond.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Even as late as 395, units with the Batavi name, although long since composed of recruits from all over the empire, were still classified as elite *palatini*, e.g. the *equites Batavi seniores* (cavalry) and *auxilium Batavi seniores* (infantry).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The revolt of the Batavi appears to have led to a significant change in the Roman government's policy on deployment of Auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The revolt proved that in times of civil strife, when legions were far from their bases campaigning for rival claimants to the imperial throne, it was dangerous to leave provinces exclusively in the hands of auxiliary regiments recruited from the indigenous nation.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] During the Julio-Claudian period, auxiliary regiments had often been deployed away from their original home province.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But in the Flavian period (69–96), this appears to have become standard policy.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Thus in AD 70, five reconstituted Batavi regiments (one **ala** and four **cohortes**) were transferred to Britain under Petillius Cerialis, who had suppressed the Civilis revolt and then embarked on the governorship of the island.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The great majority of regiments probably founded in the 1st century were stationed away from their province of origin in the second e.g. of 13 British regiments recorded in the mid-2nd century, none were stationed in Britain.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Furthermore, it appears that in the Flavian era native noblemen were no longer permitted to command auxiliary units from their own tribe.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] After a prolonged period in a foreign province a regiment would become assimilated, since the majority of its new recruits would be drawn from the province in which it was stationed, or neighbouring provinces.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Those same "British" units, mostly based on the Danube frontier, would by c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 150, after almost a century away from their home island, be largely composed of Illyrian, Thracian and Dacian recruits.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] However, there is evidence that a few regiments at least continued to draw some recruits from their original home provinces in the 2nd century e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The Flavian period also saw the first formation of large, double-size units, both infantry and cavalry, of a nominal strength of 1,000 men (*cohors/ala milliaria*), though they were actually mostly smaller (720 for an *ala milliaria* and 800 for a *cohors milliaria*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] These were the mirror image of the double-strength first cohorts of legions also introduced at this time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Such units remained a minority of the Auxilia: in the mid-2nd century, they constituted 13% of units, containing 20% of total manpower.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In 106 AD, emperor Trajan finally defeated the Dacian kingdom of Decebalus and annexed it as the Roman province of Dacia Traiana.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the mid-2nd century, there were 44 auxiliary regiments stationed there, about 10% of the total auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Together, these two provinces contained about a quarter of the total auxiliary regiments.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] There is considerable scholarly dispute about the precise size of the auxilia during the imperial era, even during the corp's best-documented period, the rule of Trajan's successor, Hadrian (117–138).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] NOTE: Manpower figures exclude officers (centurions and decurions), which would have numbered about 3,500 men overall.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In addition, Holder believes that a further 14 **cohortes**, which are attested under Trajan, immediately before Hadrian's rule, but not during or after it, probably continued in existence, giving a total of 381 units and 225,000 effectives.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The discrepancy between the two scholars is due to: (i) Interpretation of units with the same name and number, but attested in different provinces in the same period.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Spaul tends to take a more cautious approach and to assume such are the same unit moving base frequently, while Holder tends to regard them as separate units which acquired the same number due to duplicated (or even triplicated) seriation.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] (ii) Assumptions about how many **cohortes** were **equitatae**.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Spaul accepts only those **cohortes** specifically attested as **equitatae** i.e., about 40% of recorded units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Holder estimates that at least 70% of **cohortes** contained cavalry contingents by the early 2nd century.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Even according to the more conservative estimate, the auxilia were by this time significantly larger than the legions, which contained c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 155,000 effectives (28 legions of 5,500 men each) at this time, of which just 3,360 were cavalry.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] (For a detailed breakdown, see section 4: Auxilia deployment in the 2nd century, below).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] During the second half of the 2nd century, the Roman army underwent considerable further expansion, with the addition of five new legions (27,500 men) to a Principate peak of 33.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 50 regiments, although only the names of around 25–30 have survived in the epigraphic record) were probably added, possibly reaching a peak of c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] 440 regiments and around 250,000 effectives by the end of Septimius Severus's rule (211 AD).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] During the 2nd century, some units with the new names *numerus* ('group') and *vexillatio* ('detachment') appear in the diploma record.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Their size is uncertain, but was likely smaller than the regular *alae* and **cohortes**, as originally they were probably detachments from the latter, acquiring independent status after long-term separation.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] As these units are mentioned in diplomas, they were presumably part of the regular auxiliary organisation.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But *numeri* was also a generic term used for barbarian units outside the regular auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] (see section 2.4 Irregular units, below).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In 212, the *constitutio Antoniniana* (Antonine decree) of emperor Caracalla granted Roman citizenship to all the free inhabitants of the Empire – the **peregrini** – thus abolishing their second-class status.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But there is no evidence that the citizens-only rule for legions was also abolished at this time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The legions simply gained a much wider recruitment base, as they were now able to recruit any male free resident of the empire.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] Auxiliary units were now recruited mainly from Roman citizens, but probably continued to recruit non-citizen *barbari* from outside the Empire's borders.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] However, the citizens-only rule for legions appears to have been dropped some time during the 3rd century, as by the 4th-century Romans and barbarians are found serving together in all units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the mid to late 3rd century, the army was afflicted by a combination of military disasters and of pestilence, the so-called Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In 251–271, Gaul, the Alpine regions and Italy, the Balkans and the East were simultaneously overrun by Alamanni, Sarmatians, Goths and Persians respectively.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] At the same time, the Roman army was struggling with the effects of a devastating pandemic, probably of smallpox: the Plague of Cyprian, which began in 251 and was still raging in 270, when it claimed the life of emperor Claudius II Gothicus.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The evidence for an earlier pandemic, the Antonine Plague (also smallpox) indicates a mortality of 15–30% in the empire as a whole.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The armies would likely have suffered deaths at the top end of the range, due to their close concentration of individuals and frequent movements across the empire.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This probably led to a steep decline in military numbers, which only recovered at the end of the century under Diocletian (r.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The recruitment shortfall caused by the crisis seems to have led to recruitment of barbarians to the auxilia on a much greater scale than previously.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] By the 4th century, it has been estimated that some 25% of regular army recruits were barbarian-born.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the elite *palatini* regiments, anywhere between a third and a half of recruits may have been barbarian.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This is likely a much greater proportion of foreigners than joined the auxilia in the 1st and 2nd centuries.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the 3rd century, a small number of regular auxiliary units appear in the record that, for the first time, bear the names of barbarian tribes from outside the empire e.g. the *ala I Sarmatarum* attested in 3rd-century Britain.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This was probably an offshoot of the 5,500 surrendered Sarmatian horsemen posted on Hadrian's Wall by emperor Marcus Aurelius in c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This unit may be an early example of a novel process whereby irregular units of **barbari** (*foederati*) were transformed into regular auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] This process intensified in the 4th century: the **Notitia Dignitatum**, a key document on the late Roman army, lists a large number of regular units with barbarian names.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the 4th century, the Roman army underwent a radical restructuring.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In the rule of Diocletian (284–305), the traditional Principate formations of *legiones*, **alae** and **cohortes** appear to have been broken up into smaller units, many of which bore a variety of new names.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The old Principate auxilia regiments provided the basis for units at all three grades.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The *Notitia Dignitatum* lists about 70 **alae** and **cohortes** that retained their 2nd-century names, mostly *limitanei*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But traces of other auxilia regiments can be found in the *praesentales* and *comitatenses* armies.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] For example, many of the new-style *auxilia palatina* infantry regiments, considered among the best units in the army, were probably formed from old-style auxiliary **cohortes**, which they appear to closely resemble.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] The late 4th-century writer on military affairs Vegetius complains of contemporary young men joining the "auxilia" in preference to the "legions" to avoid the latter's tougher training and duties.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] But it is unclear what types of units he was referring to.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] It is possible that those older terms were still popularly used (misleadingly) to mean **limitanei** and *comitatenses* respectively.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p01] In any event, his quote in no way describes accurately the Principate auxilia, many of which were of very high quality.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The following table sets out the official, or establishment, strength of auxiliary units in the 2nd century.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The real strength of a unit would fluctuate continually, but would likely have been somewhat less than the establishment most of the time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] NOTE: Opinion is divided about the size of an *ala turma*, between 30 and 32 men.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] 30 was the size of a *turma* in the Republican cavalry and in the *cohors equitata* of the Principate auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Against this is a statement by Arrian that an **ala** was 512 strong.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This would make an *ala turma* 32 men strong.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These all-infantry units were modeled on the cohorts of the legions, with the same officers and sub-units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were typically considered to be more of a light infantry than proper legionaries.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Some auxiliaries may however have been equipped with the *lorica segmentata*, the most sophisticated legionary body armour, although scholars dispute this.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Besides this possibility, monuments (like on Trajan's Column) show auxiliaries wearing chain-mail armor, the length and form of which varied over the first and second century.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They wore helmets similar to those of the Legion.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Yet they seem to be simplified versions that were further improved over the same timeframe.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were equipped with a sword, a dagger and one or more spears or javelins.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This spear might have been a *lancea*, which can be used as a javelin as well as a thrusting spear.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Based on archeological evidences auxiliaries probably had additional lighter javelins to their *lancea*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There is no evidence that auxiliary infantry fought in a looser order than legionaries.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It appears that in a set-piece battle line, auxiliary infantry would normally be stationed on the flanks, with legionary infantry holding the centre e.g. as in the Battle of Watling Street (AD 60), the final defeat of the rebel Britons under queen Boudicca.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This was a tradition inherited from the Republic, when the precursors of auxiliary **cohortes**, the Latin **alae**, occupied the same position in the line.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The flanks of the line required equal, if not greater, skill to hold as the centre.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] During the Principate period of the Roman Empire (30 BC – AD 284), the all-mounted **Alae** ('wings') contained the elite cavalry of the army.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were specially trained in elaborate manoeuvres, such as those displayed to the emperor Hadrian during a documented inspection in Numidia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were best-suited for large-scale operations and battle, during which they acted as the primary cavalry escort for the legions, which had almost no cavalry of their own.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Roman *alares* were normally armoured, with mail or scale body armour, a cavalry version of the infantry helmet (with more protective features, such as completely covered ears) and oval shield or hexagonal.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Their weapons could be a lance, javelins, or bow and arrow but all Roman horseman had a sword (called a *spatha*) and a dagger (the *pugio*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The elite status of an *alaris* is shown by the fact that he received 20% more pay than his counterpart in an auxiliary cohort or a legionary infantryman.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The favored sources of recruitment for the cavalry of the *auxilia* were Gauls, Germans, Iberians and Thracians.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] All of these peoples had long-established skills and experience of fighting from horseback – in contrast to the Romans themselves.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The **alae** were better paid and mounted than the more numerous horsemen of the *cohortes equitatae* (see below).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These were **cohortes** with a cavalry contingent attached.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There is evidence that their numbers expanded with the passage of time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Only about 40% of attested **cohortes** are specifically attested as *equitatae* in inscriptions, which is probably the original Augustan proportion.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A study of units stationed in Syria in the mid-2nd century found that many units that did not carry the *equitata* title did in fact contain cavalrymen e.g. by discovery of a tombstone of a cavalryman attached to the cohort.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This implies that by that time, at least 70% of **cohortes** were probably **equitatae**.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The addition of cavalry to a cohort obviously enabled it to carry out a wider range of independent operations.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A *cohors equitata* was in effect a self-contained mini-army.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The traditional view of *equites cohortales* (the cavalry arm of **cohortes equitatae**), as expounded by G.L.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Cheesman, was that they were just a mounted infantry with poor-quality horses.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They would use their mounts simply to reach the battlefield and then would dismount to fight.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Although it is clear that **equites cohortales** did not match *equites alares* (*ala* cavalrymen) in quality (hence their lower pay), the evidence is that they fought as cavalry in the same way as the **alares** and often alongside them.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Their armour and weapons were the same as for the *alares*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Nevertheless, non-combat roles of the **equites cohortales** differed significantly from the **alares**.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Non-combat roles such as despatch riders (*dispositi*) were generally filled by cohort cavalry.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the Republican period, the standard trio of specialised auxilia were Balearic slingers, Cretan archers and Numidian light cavalry.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These functions, plus some new ones, continued in the 2nd-century auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were known as the *equites Maurorum* or *Numidarum* ('Moorish or Numidian cavalry').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] On Trajan's Column, Mauri horsemen, depicted with long hair in dreadlocks, are shown riding their small but resilient horses bare-back and unbridled, with a simple braided rope round their mount's neck for control.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They wear no body or head armour, carrying only a small, round leather shield.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Their weaponry cannot be discerned due to stone erosion, but is known from Livy to have consisted of several short javelins.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Exceptionally fast and maneuverable, Numidian cavalry would harass the enemy by hit-and-run attacks, riding up and loosing volleys of javelins, then scattering faster than any opposing cavalry could pursue.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were superbly suited to scouting, harassment, ambush and pursuit.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It is unclear what proportion of the Numidian cavalry were regular auxilia units as opposed to irregular **foederati** units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the 3rd century, new formations of light cavalry appear, apparently recruited from the Danubian provinces: the *equites Dalmatae* ('Dalmatian cavalry').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Little is known about these, but they were prominent in the 4th century, with several units listed in the *Notitia Dignitatum*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A unit of *dromedarii* ('camel-mounted troops') is attested from the 2nd century, the *ala I Ulpia dromedariorum milliaria* in Syria.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A substantial number of auxiliary regiments (32, or about 1 in 12 in the 2nd century) were denoted *sagittariorum*, or archer-units (from *[[sagittarii|*sagittarii*]]* lit.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These 32 units (of which four were double-strength) had a total official strength of 17,600 men.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] All three types of auxiliary regiment (**ala**, *cohors* and *cohors equitata*) could be denoted *sagittariorum*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Although these units evidently specialised in archery, it is uncertain from the available evidence whether all **sagittariorum** personnel were archers, or simply a higher proportion than in ordinary units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] At the same time, ordinary regiments probably also possessed some archers, otherwise their capacity for independent operations would have been unduly constrained.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Bas reliefs appear to show personnel in ordinary units employing bows.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] From about 218 BC onwards, the archers of the Roman army of the mid-Republic were virtually all mercenaries from the island of Crete, which boasted a long specialist tradition.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] During the late Republic (88–30 BC) and the Augustan period, Crete was gradually eclipsed by men from other, much more populous, regions subjugated by the Romans with strong archery traditions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These included Thrace, Anatolia and, above all, Syria.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Of the 32 *sagittarii* units attested in the mid-2nd century, thirteen have Syrian names, seven Thracian, five from Anatolia, one from Crete and the remaining six of other or uncertain origin.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Three distinct types of archers are shown on Trajan's Column: (a) with scalar cuirass, conical steel helmet and cloak; (b) without armour, with cloth conical cap and long tunic; or (c) equipped in the same way as general auxiliary foot-soldiers (apart from carrying bows instead of javelins).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The first type were probably Syrian or Anatolian units; the third type probably Thracian.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The standard bow used by Roman auxilia was the recurved composite bow, a sophisticated, compact and powerful weapon.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] From about 218 BC onwards, the Republican army's slingers were exclusively mercenaries from the Balearic Islands, which had nurtured a strong indigenous tradition of slinging from prehistoric times.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] As a result, in classical Latin, *Baleares* (literally 'inhabitants of the Balearic Islands') became an alternative word for 'slingers' (*funditores*, from *funda* 'sling').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Because of this, it is uncertain whether most of the imperial army's slingers continued to be drawn from the Balearics themselves, or, like archers, derived mainly from other regions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Independent slinger units are not attested in the epigraphic record of the Principate.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] However, slingers are portrayed on Trajan's Column.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They are shown unarmoured, wearing a short tunic.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They carry a cloth bag, slung in front, to hold their shot (*glandes*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Throughout the Principate period, there is evidence of ethnic units of *barbari* outside the normal auxilia organisation fighting alongside Roman troops.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] To an extent, these units were simply a continuation of the old client-king levies of the late Republic: ad hoc bodies of troops supplied by Rome's puppet petty-kings on the imperial borders for particular campaigns.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Some clearly remained in Roman service beyond the campaigns, keeping their own native leadership, attire and equipment and structure.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These units were known to the Romans as *socii* ('allies'), *symmachiarii* (from *symmachoi*, Greek for 'allies') or *foederati* ('treaty troops' from *foedus*, 'treaty').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] One estimate puts the number of *foederati* in the time of Trajan at about 11,000, divided into about 40 **numeri** (units) of about 300 men each.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The purpose of employing **foederati** units was to use their specialist fighting skills.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Many of these would have been troops of Numidian cavalry (see light cavalry above).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The **foederati** make their first official appearance on Trajan's Column, where they are portrayed in a standardised manner, with long hair and beards, barefoot, stripped to the waist, wearing long trousers held up by wide belts and wielding clubs.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In reality, several different tribes supported the Romans in the Dacian wars.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Their attire and weapons would have varied widely.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The Column stereotypes them with the appearance of a single tribe, probably the most outlandish-looking, to differentiate them clearly from the regular auxilia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Judging by the frequency of their appearance in the Column's battle scenes, the **foederati** were important contributors to the Roman operations in Dacia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Another example of **foederati** are the 5,500 captured Sarmatian cavalrymen sent by Emperor Marcus Aurelius (r.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] 161–180) to garrison a fort on Hadrian's Wall after their defeat in the Marcomannic Wars.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The evidence for auxiliary ranks and pay is scant: even less exists than the patchy evidence for their legionary counterparts.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There seems to be some consensus, however, that the auxiliary was paid one third of what a legionary received: 300 sesterces a year (400 after the reign of the emperor Commodus).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Both auxiliaries and seamen received the *viaticum* of 300 sesterces, although the various sources differ as to whether auxiliaries and sailors received the retirement bonus known as the *honesta missio*, or honorable discharge.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] At the bottom end of the rank pyramid, rankers were known as *caligati* (lit.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] 'sandal men' from the *caligae* or hob-nailed sandals worn by soldiers).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Depending on the type of regiment they belonged to, they held the official ranks of *pedes* (foot soldier in a *cohors*), *eques* (cavalryman in a *cohors equitata*) and *gregalis* (*ala* cavalryman).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] During the Principate, recruitment into the legions was restricted to Roman citizens only.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This rule, which derived from the pre-Social War Republican army, was strictly enforced.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The few exceptions recorded, such as during emergencies and for the illegitimate sons of legionaries, do not warrant the suggestion that the rule was routinely ignored.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the 1st century, the vast majority of auxiliary common soldiers were recruited from the Roman *peregrini* (second-class citizens).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the Julio-Claudian era, conscription of *peregrini* seems to have been practiced alongside voluntary recruitment, probably in the form of a fixed proportion of men reaching military age in each tribe being drafted.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] From the Flavian era onwards, the auxilia were an all-volunteer force.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Although recruits as young as 14 are recorded, the majority of recruits (66%) were from the 18–23 age group.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] When it was first raised, an auxiliary regiment would have been recruited from the native tribe or people whose name it bore.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the early Julio-Claudian period, it seems that efforts were made to preserve the ethnic integrity of units, even when the regiment was posted in a faraway province.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] But in the later part of the period, recruitment in the region where the regiment was posted increased and became predominant from the Flavian era onwards.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The regiment would thus lose its original ethnic identity.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The unit's name would thus become a mere curiosity devoid of meaning, although some of its members might inherit foreign names from their veteran ancestors.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This view has to be qualified, however, as evidence from military diplomas and other inscriptions shows that some units continued to recruit in their original home areas e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Batavi units stationed in Britain, where some units had an international membership.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It also appears that the Danubian provinces (Raetia, Pannonia, Moesia, Dacia) remained key recruiting grounds for units stationed all over the empire.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Researchers have often assumed that Roman citizens were also regularly recruited to the auxilia because various sources record auxiliary soldiers with the Tria nomina.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Explanations for that phenomenon include that sons of auxiliary veterans preferred to join their fathers' old regiments, which were a kind of extended family to them, rather than join a much larger, unfamiliar legion.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] However, it has been shown that many of the auxiliary soldiers with tria nomina were not full Roman citizens that could enter a legion, but only had Latin citizenship or belonged (as sons of freedmen) to the "Latini Iuniani".
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There are, however, also instances of legionaries transferring to the auxilia (to a higher rank).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] After the grant of citizenship to all **peregrini** in 212, auxiliary regiments became predominantly citizen units.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Less clearcut is the question of whether the regular auxilia recruited *barbari* (barbarians, as the Romans called people living outside the empire's borders).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Although there is little evidence of it before the 3rd century, the consensus is that auxilia recruited barbarians throughout their history.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the 3rd century, a few auxilia units of clearly barbarian origin start to appear in the record e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *Ala I Sarmatarum*, *cuneus Frisiorum* and *numerus Hnaufridi* in Britain.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There existed a hierarchy of pay between types of auxiliary, with cavalry higher paid than infantry.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] One recent estimate is that in the time of Augustus, the annual pay structure was: *eques alaris* (*gregalis*) 263 *denarii*, *eques cohortalis* 225, and *cohors* infantryman 188.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The same differentials (of about 20% between grades) seem to have existed at the time of Domitian (r.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] However, Goldsworthy points out that the common assumption that rates of pay were universal across provinces and units is unproven.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Pay may have varied according to the origin of the unit.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Gross salary was subject to deductions for food, clothing, boots and hay (probably for the company mules).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It is unclear whether the cost of armour and weapons was also deducted, or borne by the army.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Deductions left the soldier with a net salary of 78 **denarii**.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This sum was sufficient, on the basis of the food deduction, to amply feed an adult for a year.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In 84 AD Domitian increased basic legionary pay by 33% (from 225 to 300 **denarii**): a similar increase was presumably accorded to auxiliaries, boosting their net income to 140 **denarii**, i.e. more than two food allowances.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It was entirely disposable, as the soldier was exempt from the poll tax (*capitatio*), did not pay rent (he was housed in fort barracks) and his food, clothing and equipment were already deducted.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It should be borne in mind that most recruits came from peasant families living at subsistence level.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] To such persons, any disposable income would appear attractive.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It could be spent on leisure activities, sent to relatives or simply saved for retirement.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There is no evidence that auxiliaries received the substantial cash bonuses (donativum) handed to legionaries on the accession of a new emperor and other occasions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Although irregular, these payments (each worth 75 **denarii** to a common legionary) averaged once every 7.5 years in the early 1st century and every three years later.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Duncan-Jones has suggested that *donativa* may have been paid to auxiliaries also from the time of Hadrian onwards, on the grounds that the total amount of donative to the military increased sharply at that time.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A very valuable benefit paid to legionaries was the discharge bonus (*praemia*) paid on completion of the full 25 years' service.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] At 3,000 **denarii**, this was equivalent to ten years' gross salary for a common legionary after the pay increase of 84 AD.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] It would enable him to purchase a substantial plot of land.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Again, there is no indication that auxiliaries were paid a discharge bonus.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] For auxiliaries, the discharge bonus was the grant of Roman citizenship, which carried important tax exemptions.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] However, Duncan-Jones argues that the fact that service in the auxilia was competitive with the legions (deduced from the many Roman citizens that joined the auxilia) that a discharge bonus may have been paid.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Below centurion/decurion rank, junior officers in the Roman army were known as *principales*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] An auxiliary cohort's ranks appear the same as in a legionary *centuria*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These were, in ascending order: *tesserarius* ('officer of the watch'), *signifer* (standard-bearer for the *centuria*), *optio* (centurion's deputy) and *vexillarius* (standard-bearer for the whole regiment, from *vexillum*).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the *turmae* of **cohortes equitatae** (and of **alae**?), the decurion's second-in-command was probably known as a *curator*, responsible for horses and caparison.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] As in the legions, the *principales*, together with some regimental specialists, were classified in two pay-scales: *sesquiplicarii* ('one-and-a-half-pay men') and *duplicarii* ('double-pay men').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] These ranks are probably most closely resembled by the modern ranks of corporal and sergeant respectively.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Besides combat effectives, regiments also contained specialists, the most senior of whom were *sesquiplicarii* or *duplicarii*, the rest common soldiers with the status of *milities immunes* ('exempt soldiers' i.e. exempt from normal duties).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Ranking specialists included the *medicus* (regimental doctor), *veterinarius* (veterinary doctor, in charge of the care of horses, pack animals and livestock), *custos armorum* (keeper of the armoury), and the *cornicularius* (clerk in charge of all the regiment's records and paperwork).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The limited evidence on auxiliary **centuriones** and *decuriones* is that such officers could be directly commissioned as well as promoted from the ranks.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Many appear to have come from provincial aristocracies.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Those rising from the ranks could be promotions from the legions as well as from the regiment's own ranks.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the Julio-Claudian period auxiliary *centuriones* and **decuriones** were a roughly equal split between citizens and **peregrini**, though later citizens became predominant due to the spread of citizenship among military families.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Because **centuriones** and **decuriones** often rose from the ranks, they have often been compared to warrant officers such as sergeants major in modern armies.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] However, centurions' social role was much wider than a modern warrant officer.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In addition to their military duties, centurions performed a wide range of administrative tasks, which was necessary in the absence of an adequate bureaucracy to support provincial governors.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] They were also relatively wealthy, due to their high salaries (see table above).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] However, most of the surviving evidence concerns legionary centurions and it is uncertain whether their auxiliary counterparts shared their high status and non-military role.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There is little evidence about the pay-scales of auxiliary **centuriones** and **decuriones**, but these are also believed to have amounted to several times that of a *miles*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Unlike a *legatus legionis* (who had an officer staff of six *tribuni militum* and one *praefectus castrorum*), an auxiliary **praefectus** does not appear to have enjoyed the support of purely staff officers.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The possible exception is an attested *beneficiarius* ('deputy'), who may have been the *praefectus*' second-in-command, if this title was a regular rank and not simply an ad hoc appointment for a specific task.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Also attached to the **praefectus** were the regiment's *vexillarius* (standard-bearer for the whole unit) and *cornucen* (horn-blower).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] From a survey by Devijver of persons whose origin can be determined, it appears that during the 1st century, the large majority (65%) of auxiliary prefects were of Italian origin.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The Italian proportion dropped steadily, to 38% in the 2nd century, and 21% in the 3rd century.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] 41–54) only Roman knights were eligible to hold command of an auxiliary regiment.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Equestrians by birth would normally begin their military careers at c.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] An axillary had to do 25 years of service before joining the army.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Commands were held in a set sequence, each held for 3–4 years: prefect of an auxiliary **cohors**, **tribunus militum** in a legion and finally prefect of an auxiliary **ala**.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In Hadrian's time, a fourth command was added, for exceptionally able officers, of prefect of an *ala milliaria*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Like officers senatorial rank, hereditary equestrians held civilian posts before and after their decade of military service, whereas non-hereditary officers tended to remain in the army, commanding various units in various provinces.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] By the 3rd century, most auxiliary prefects had exclusively military careers.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The pay of a **praefectus** of an auxiliary regiment in the early 2nd century has been estimated at over 50 times that of a *miles* (common soldier).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] (This compares to a full colonel in the British Army, who is currently paid about five times a private's salary).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The reason for the huge gap between the top and the bottom of the pyramid is that Roman society was far more hierarchical than a modern one.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A **praefectus** was not just a senior officer.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] He was also a Roman citizen (which most of his men were not) and, as a member of the equestrian order, an aristocrat.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The social gulf between the **praefectus** and a *peregrinus* soldier was thus immense, and the pay differential reflected that fact.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The nomenclature of the great majority of regiments followed a standard configuration: unit type, followed by serial number, followed by name of the **peregrini** tribe (or nation) from whom the regiment was originally raised, in the genitive plural case e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *cohors III Batavorum* ('3rd Cohort of Batavi'); *cohors I Brittonum* ('1st Cohort of Britons').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Some regiments combine the names of two **peregrini** tribes, most likely after the merger of two previously separate regiments e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *ala I Pannoniorum et Gallorum* ('1st Wing of Pannonii and Gauls').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] A minority of regiments are named after an individual, mostly after the first prefect of the regiment, e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *ala Sulpicia* (presumably named after a prefect whose middle (*gens*) name was Sulpicius).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The latter is also an example of a regiment that did not have a serial number.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Regiments were often rewarded for meritorious service by the grant of an honorific title.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The most sought-after was the prestigious *c.R.* (*civium Romanorum* 'of Roman citizens') title.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] In the latter case, all the regiment's members at the time, but not their successors, would be granted Roman citizenship.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] But the regiment would retain the *c.R*. title in perpetuity.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Another common title was the *gens* name of the emperor making the award (or founding the regiment) e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *Ulpia*: the **gens** name of Trajan (Marcus Ulpius Traianus r.98–117).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Other titles were similar to those given to the legions e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *pia fidelis* (*p.f.* 'dutiful and loyal').
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The Roman army awarded a variety of individual decorations (*dona*) for valour to its legionaries.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *Hasta pura* was a miniature spear; *phalerae* were large medal-like bronze or silver discs worn on the cuirass; *armillae* were bracelets worn on the wrist; and torques were worn round the neck, or on the cuirass.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The highest awards were the *coronae* ('crowns'), of which the most prestigious was the *corona civica*, a crown made of oak leaves awarded for saving the life of a Roman citizen in battle.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The most valuable award was the *corona muralis*, a crown made of gold awarded to the first man to scale an enemy rampart.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] This was awarded rarely, as such a man hardly ever survived.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] There is no evidence that auxiliary common soldiers received individual decorations, although auxiliary officers did.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Instead, the whole regiment was honoured by a title reflecting the type of award e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *torquata* (awarded a torque) or *armillata* (awarded bracelets).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Some regiments would, in the course of time, accumulate a long list of titles and decorations e.g.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] *cohors I Brittonum Ulpia torquata pia fidelis c.R.*.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Notes: (1) Table excludes about 2,000 officers (centurions and above).
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The table shows that legions did not have a standard complement of auxiliary regiments and that there was no fixed ratio of auxiliary regiments to legions in each province.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The ratio varied from six regiments per legion in Cappadocia to 40 per legion in Mauretania.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Overall, cavalry represented about 20% (including the small contingents of legionary cavalry) of the total army effectives.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] But there were variations: in Mauretania the cavalry proportion was 28%.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] The figures show the massive deployments in Britannia and Dacia.
[src:siege-hook/auxilia-p02] Together, these two provinces account for 27% of the total auxilia corps.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] These accounts were written by various authors throughout and after the history of the Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Following the First Punic War, naval battles were less significant than land battles to the military history of Rome due to its encompassment of lands of the periphery and its unchallenged dominance of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The Roman army battled first against its tribal neighbours and Etruscan towns within Italy, and later came to dominate the Mediterranean and at its height the provinces of Britannia and Asia Minor.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] As with most ancient civilizations, Rome's military served the triple purpose of securing its borders, exploiting peripheral areas through measures such as imposing tribute on conquered peoples, and maintaining internal order.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] From the outset, Rome's military typified this pattern, and the majority of Rome's campaigns were characterised by one of two types.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The first is the territorial expansionist campaign, normally begun as a counter-offensive, in which each victory brought subjugation of large areas of territory and allowed Rome to grow from a small town to a population of 55 million in the early empire when expansion was halted.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The second is the civil war, which plagued Rome from its foundation to its eventual demise.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Despite their formidable reputation and host of victories, Roman armies were not invincible.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Romans "produced their share of incompetents" who led Roman armies into catastrophic defeats.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Nevertheless, it was generally the fate of even the greatest of Rome's enemies, such as Pyrrhus and Hannibal, to win the battle but lose the war.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The history of Rome's campaigning is, if nothing else, a history of obstinate persistence overcoming appalling losses.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Knowledge of Roman history stands apart from other civilizations in the ancient world.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Its chronicles, military and otherwise, document the city's very foundation to its eventual demise.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Although some histories have been lost, such as Trajan's account of the Dacian Wars, and others, such as Rome's earliest histories, are at least semi-apocryphal, the extant histories of Rome's military history are extensive.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Rome's earliest history, from the time of its founding as a small tribal village, to the downfall of its kings, is the least well preserved.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Although the early Romans were literate to some degree, this void may be due to the lack of will to record their history at that time, or such histories as they did record were lost.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Although the Roman historian Livy (59 BC – 17 AD) lists a series of seven kings of early Rome in his work *Ab urbe condita*, from its establishment through its earliest years, the first four kings (Romulus, Numa, Tullus Hostilius and Ancus Marcius) may be apocryphal.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] A number of points of view have been proposed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Grant and others argue that prior to the establishment of the Etruscan kingdom of Rome under the traditional fifth king, Tarquinius Priscus, Rome would have been led by a religious leader of some sort.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Very little is known of Rome's military history from this era, and what history has come down to us is more legendary than factual.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Traditionally, Romulus fortified the Palatine Hill after founding the city, and shortly thereafter Rome was "*equal to any of the surrounding cities in her prowess in war*".
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The first of the campaigns fought by the Romans in this legendary account are the wars with various Latin cities and the Sabines.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] According to Livy, the Latin village of Caenina responded to the event of the abduction of the Sabine women by invading Roman territory, but were routed and their village captured.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The Latins of Antemnae and those of Crustumerium were defeated next in a similar fashion.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The remaining main body of the Sabines attacked Rome and briefly captured the citadel, but were then convinced to conclude a treaty with the Romans under which the Sabines became Roman citizens.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] There was a further war in the 8th century BC against Fidenae and Veii.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] In the 7th century BC there was a war with Alba Longa, a second war with Fidenae and Veii and a second Sabine War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Ancus Marcius led Rome to victory against the Latins and, according to the Fasti Triumphales, over the Veientes and Sabines also.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Lucius Tarquinius Priscus' first war was waged against the Latins.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquinius took the Latin town of Apiolae by storm and took great booty from there back to Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] According to the *Fasti Triumphales*, the war occurred prior to 588 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] His military ability was tested by an attack from the Sabines.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquinius doubled the numbers of equites to help the war effort, and defeat the Sabines.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] In the peace negotiations that followed, Tarquinius received the town of Collatia and appointed his nephew, Arruns Tarquinius, also known as *Egerius*, as commander of the garrison which he stationed in that city.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquinius returned to Rome and celebrated a triumph for his victories that, according to the *Fasti Triumphales*, occurred on 13 September 585 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Subsequently, the Latin cities of Corniculum, old Ficulea, Cameria, Crustumerium, Ameriola, Medullia and Nomentum were subdued and became Roman.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Early in his reign, Servius Tullius warred against Veii and the Etruscans.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] He is said to have shown valour in the campaign, and to have routed a great army of the enemy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The war helped him to cement his position at Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] According to the *Fasti Triumphales*, Servius celebrated three triumphs over the Etruscans, including on 25 November 571 BC and 25 May 567 BC (the date of the third triumph is not legible on the *Fasti*).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] This was done, and Tarquin formed combined units of Roman and Latin troops.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquin next began a war against the Volsci.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] He took the wealthy town of Suessa Pometia, with the spoils of which he commenced the erection of the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus which his father had vowed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] He also celebrated a triumph for his victory.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] He was next engaged in a war with Gabii, one of the Latin cities, which had rejected the Latin treaty with Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Unable to take the city by force of arms, Tarquin had his son, Sextus Tarquinius, infiltrate the city, gain the trust of its people and command of its army.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] In time he killed or exiled the city's leaders, and handed control of the city over to his father.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquin also agreed to a peace with the Aequi, and renewed the treaty of peace between Rome and the Etruscans.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] According to the Fasti Triumphales, Tarquin also won a victory over the Sabines.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquinius later went to war with the Rutuli.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] According to Livy, the Rutuli were, at that time, a very wealthy nation.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquinius was desirous of obtaining the booty which would come with victory over the Rutuli.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] Tarquin unsuccessfully sought to take the Rutulian capital, Ardea, by storm, and subsequently began an extensive siege of the city.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The war was interrupted by the revolution which overthrew the Roman monarchy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] The Roman army, camped outside Ardea, welcomed Lucius Junius Brutus as their new leader, and expelled the king's sons.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p01] It is unclear what was the outcome of the siege, or indeed the war.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The first non-apocryphal Roman wars were wars of both expansion and defence, aimed at protecting Rome itself from neighbouring cities and nations and establishing its territory in the region.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the semi-legendary period of the early republic, sources record Rome was twice attacked by Etruscan armies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] About 509 BC war with Veii and Tarquinii was said to have been instigated by the recently overthrown king Tarquinius Superbus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Again in 508 BC Tarquin persuaded the king of Clusium, Lars Porsenna, to wage war on Rome, resulting in a siege of Rome and afterwards a peace treaty.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Initially, Rome's immediate neighbours were either Latin towns and villages on a tribal system similar to that of Rome, or else tribal Sabines from the Apennine hills beyond.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] One by one, Rome defeated both the persistent Sabines and the local cities that were either under Etruscan control or else Latin towns that had cast off their Etruscan rulers, as had Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After defeating the Veientes, the Romans had effectively completed the conquest of their immediate Etruscan neighbours, as well as secured their position against the immediate threat posed by the tribespeople of the Apennine hills.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the meantime, it also affected the agriculture as well as diet regime of the empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Since the enlargement the population in Apennine peninsula had increased and led to certain changes in agriculture, such as switch to goat breeding from cattle, indicating higher levels of protein supply in the diet which played a crucial role in stature of the locals.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, Rome still controlled only a very limited area and the affairs of Rome were minor even to those in Italy and Rome's affairs were only just coming to the attention of the Greeks, the dominant cultural force at the time.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] At this point the bulk of Italy remained in the hands of Latin, Sabine, Samnite and other peoples in the central part of Italy, Greek colonies to the south, and the Celtic people, including the Gauls, to the north.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By 390 BC, several Gallic tribes had begun invading Italy from the north as their culture expanded throughout Europe.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Clusians, overwhelmed by the size of the enemy in numbers and ferocity, called on Rome for help.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Perhaps unintentionally the Romans found themselves not just in conflict with the Senones, but their primary target.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Romans met them in pitched battle at the Battle of the Allia around 390–387 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Gauls, under their chieftain Brennus, defeated the Roman army of around 15,000 troops and proceeded to pursue the fleeing Romans back to Rome itself and partially sacked the town before being either driven off or bought off.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] They were probably defeated by the exiled dictator Marcus Furius Camillus who gathered the scattered Roman forces that consisted partly of fugitives and partly those who had survived the battle of Alia, and marched to Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] According to tradition, he took the Gauls by surprise, when Brennus, having tricked the weights in which the gold rescue that had been set for the city was measured, uttered the expression Vae Victis!
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] (Woe to the losers!); Camillus claimed that, since he was a dictator, no agreement was valid without his acquiescence, so no ransom was due and he answered Breno with another famous phrase: 'Non auro sed ferro liberanda est patria' (It is with iron, not with gold, how the homeland is released).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After defeating the Gauls in the subsequent battle, he entered the city in triumph, greeted by his fellow citizens as alter Romulus (the other Romulus), pater patriae (father of the homeland) and conditor alter urbis (second founder of the city).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Celtic problem would not be resolved for Rome until the final subjugation of all Gaul following the Battle of Alesia in 52 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After swiftly recovering from the sack of Rome, the Romans immediately resumed their expansion within Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Despite their successes, their mastery of the whole of Italy was by no means assured.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Samnites were a people just as martial and as rich as the Romans and had the objective of their own to secure more lands in the fertile Italian plains on which Rome itself lay.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome was therefore forced to contend by around 340 BC against both Samnite incursions into their territory and, simultaneously, in a bitter war against their former allies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome bested the Latins in the Battle of Vesuvius and again in the Battle of Trifanum, after which the Latin cities were obliged to submit to Roman rule.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Perhaps due to Rome's lenient treatment of their defeated foe, the Latins submitted largely amicably to Roman rule for the next 200 years.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Second Samnite War, from 327 BC to 304 BC, was a much longer and more serious affair for both the Romans and Samnites, running for over twenty years and incorporating twenty-four battles that led to massive casualties on both sides.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The fortunes of the two sides fluctuated throughout its course: the Samnites seized Neapolis in the Capture of Neapolis in 327 BC, which the Romans then re-captured before losing at the Battle of the Caudine Forks and the Battle of Lautulae.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Romans then proved victorious at the Battle of Bovianum and the tide turned strongly against the Samnites from 314 BC onwards, leading them to sue for peace with progressively less generous terms.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By 304 BC the Romans had effectively annexed the greater degree of the Samnite territory, founding several colonies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] This pattern of meeting aggression in force and so inadvertently gaining territory in strategic counter-attacks was to become a common feature of Roman military history.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Seven years after their defeat, with Roman dominance of the area looking assured, the Samnites rose again and defeated the Romans at the Battle of Camerinum in 298 BC, to open the Third Samnite War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] With this success in hand they managed to bring together a coalition of several previous enemies of Rome, all of whom were probably keen to prevent any one faction dominating the entire region.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The army that faced the Romans at the Battle of Sentinum in 295 BC included Samnites, Gauls, Etruscans and Umbrians.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] When the Roman army won a convincing victory over these combined forces it must have become clear that little could prevent Roman dominance of Italy and in the Battle of Populonia (282 BC) Rome destroyed the last vestiges of Etruscan power in the region.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By the beginning of the 3rd century Rome had established itself as a major power on the Italian Peninsula, but had not yet come into conflict with the dominant military powers in the Mediterranean at the time: Carthage and the Greek kingdoms.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome had all but completely defeated the Samnites, mastered its fellow Latin towns, and greatly reduced Etruscan power in the region.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, the south of Italy was controlled by the Greek colonies of Magna Grecia who had been allied to the Samnites, and continued Roman expansion brought the two into inevitable conflict.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the naval Battle of Thurii, Tarentum appealed for military aid to Pyrrhus, ruler of Epirus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Roman army had not yet seen elephants in battle, and their inexperience turned the tide in Pyrrhus' favour at the Battle of Heraclea in 280 BC, and again at the Battle of Ausculum in 279 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Despite these victories, Pyrrhus found his position in Italy untenable.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome steadfastly refused to negotiate with Pyrrhus as long as his army remained in Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Furthermore, Rome entered into a treaty of support with Carthage, and Pyrrhus found that despite his expectations, none of the other Italic peoples would defect to the Greek and Samnite cause.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Facing unacceptably heavy losses with each encounter with the Roman army, and failing to find further allies in Italy, Pyrrhus withdrew from the peninsula and campaigned in Sicily against Carthage, abandoning his allies to deal with the Romans.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] When his Sicilian campaign was also ultimately a failure, and at the request of his Italian allies, Pyrrhus returned to Italy to face Rome once more.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 275 BC, Pyrrhus again met the Roman army at the Battle of Beneventum.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] This time the Romans had devised methods to deal with the war elephants, including the use of javelins, fire and, one source claims, simply hitting the elephants heavily on the head.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] While Beneventum was indecisive, Pyrrhus realised that his army had been exhausted and reduced by years of foreign campaigns, and seeing little hope for further gains, he withdrew completely from Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The conflicts with Pyrrhus would have a great effect on Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] It had shown that it was capable of pitting its armies successfully against the dominant military powers of the Mediterranean, and further showed that the Greek kingdoms were incapable of defending their colonies in Italy and abroad.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome quickly moved into southern Italia, subjugating and dividing Magna Grecia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Effectively dominating the Italian peninsula, and with a proven international military reputation, Rome now began to look to expand from the Italian mainland.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Since the Alps formed a natural barrier to the north, and Rome was none too keen to meet the fierce Gauls in battle once more, the city's gaze turned to Sicily and the islands of the Mediterranean, a policy that would bring it into direct conflict with its former ally Carthage.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome first began to make war outside the Italian peninsula during the Punic wars against Carthage, a former Phoenician colony that had established on the north coast of Africa and developed into a powerful state.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After the defeat of the Seleucid Emperor Antiochus III the Great in the Roman-Syrian War (Treaty of Apamea, 188 BC) in the eastern sea, Rome emerged as the dominant Mediterranean power and the most powerful city in the classical world.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The First Punic War began in 264 BC when settlements on Sicily began to appeal to the two powers between which they lay – Rome and Carthage – in order to solve internal conflicts.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The willingness of both Rome and Carthage to become embroiled on the soil of a third party may indicate a willingness to test each other's power without wishing to enter a full war of annihilation; certainly there was considerable disagreement within Rome about whether to prosecute the war at all.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The war saw land battles in Sicily early on, such as the Battle of Agrigentum, but the theatre shifted to naval battles around Sicily and Africa.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] For the Romans, naval warfare was a relatively unexplored concept.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Before the First Punic War in 264 BC there was no Roman navy to speak of, as all previous Roman wars had been fought on land in Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The new war in Sicily against Carthage, a great naval power, forced Rome to quickly build a fleet and train sailors.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome took to naval warfare "like a brick to water" and the first few naval battles of the First Punic War such as the Battle of the Lipari Islands were catastrophic disasters for Rome, as might fairly be expected from a city that had no real prior experience of naval warfare.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, after training more sailors and inventing a grappling engine known as a Corvus, a Roman naval force under C.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Duillius was able to roundly defeat a Carthaginian fleet at the Battle of Mylae.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In just four years, a state without any real naval experience had managed to better a major regional maritime power in battle.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Further naval victories followed at the Battle of Tyndaris and the Battle of Cape Ecnomus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After having won control of the seas, a Roman force landed on the African coast under Marcus Regulus, who was at first victorious, winning the Battle of Adys and forcing Carthage to sue for peace.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, the terms of peace that Rome proposed were so heavy that negotiations failed, and in response, the Carthaginians hired Xanthippus of Carthage, a mercenary from the martial Greek city-state of Sparta, to reorganise and lead their army.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Xanthippus managed to cut off the Roman army from its base by re-establishing Carthaginian naval supremacy and then defeated and captured Regulus at the Battle of Tunis.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Despite being defeated on African soil, the Romans with their newfound naval abilities, roundly beat the Carthaginians in naval battle again – largely through the tactical innovations of the Roman fleet – at the Battle of the Aegates Islands.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Carthage was left without a fleet or sufficient coin to raise a new one.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] For a maritime power, the loss of their access to the Mediterranean stung financially and psychologically, and the Carthaginians again sued for peace, during which negotiations, Rome battled the *Ligures* tribe in the Ligurian War and the *Insubres* in the Gallic War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Continuing distrust led to the renewal of hostilities in the Second Punic War when Hannibal, a member of the Barcid family of Carthaginian nobility, attacked Saguntum, a city with diplomatic ties to Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Hannibal then raised an army in Iberia and famously crossed the Italian Alps with elephants to invade Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the first battle on Italian soil at Ticinus in 218 BC Hannibal defeated the Romans under Scipio the Elder in a small cavalry fight.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the three battles of Nola, Roman general Marcus Claudius Marcellus managed to hold off Hannibal but then Hannibal smashed a succession of Roman consular armies at the First Battle of Capua, the Battle of the Silarus, the Second Battle of Herdonia, the Battle of Numistro and the Battle of Asculum.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By this time Hannibal's brother Hasdrubal Barca sought to cross the Alps into Italy and join his brother with a second army.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Despite being defeated in Iberia in the Battle of Baecula, Hasdrubal managed to break through into Italy only to be defeated decisively by Gaius Claudius Nero and Marcus Livius Salinator on the Metaurus River.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Unable to defeat Hannibal himself on Italian soil, and with Hannibal savaging the Italian countryside but unwilling or unable to destroy Rome itself, the Romans boldly sent an army to Africa with the intention of threatening the Carthaginian capital.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 203 BC at the Battle of Bagbrades the invading Roman army under Scipio Africanus Major defeated the Carthaginian army of Hasdrubal Gisco and Syphax and Hannibal was recalled to Africa.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] At the famous Battle of Zama Scipio decisively defeated – perhaps even "annihilated" – Hannibal's army in North Africa, ending the Second Punic War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Carthage never managed to recover after the Second Punic War and the Third Punic War that followed was in reality a simple punitive mission to raze the city of Carthage to the ground.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Carthage was almost defenceless and when besieged offered immediate surrender, conceding to a string of outrageous Roman demands.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Romans refused the surrender, demanding as their further terms of surrender the complete destruction of the city and, seeing little to lose, the Carthaginians prepared to fight.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the Battle of Carthage the city was stormed after a short siege and completely destroyed, its culture "almost totally extinguished".
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome's conflict with the Carthaginians in the Punic Wars led them into expansion in the Iberian Peninsula of modern-day Spain and Portugal.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Punic empire of the Carthaginian Barcid family consisted of territories in Iberia, many of which Rome gained control of during the Punic Wars.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Italy remained the main theatre of war for much of the Second Punic War, but the Romans also aimed to destroy the Barcid Empire in Iberia and prevent major Punic allies from linking up with forces in Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Over the years, Rome had expanded along the southern Iberian coast until in 211 BC it captured the city of Saguntum.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Following two major military expeditions to Iberia, the Romans finally crushed Carthaginian control of the peninsula in 206 BC, at the Battle of Ilipa, and the peninsula became a Roman province known as Hispania.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] From 206 BC onwards the only opposition to Roman control of the peninsula came from within the native Celtiberian tribes themselves, whose disunity prevented their security from Roman expansion.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Following two small-scale rebellions in 197 BC, in 195–194 BC war broke out between the Romans and the Lusitani people in the Lusitanian War, in modern-day Portugal.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By 179 BC, the Romans had mostly succeeded in pacifying the region and bringing it under their control.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] About 154 BC, a major revolt was re-ignited in Numantia, which is known as the First Numantine War, and a long war of resistance was fought between the advancing forces of the Roman Republic and the Lusitani tribes of Hispania.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The praetor Servius Sulpicius Galba and the proconsul Lucius Licinius Lucullus arrived in 151 BC and began the process of subduing the local population.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 150 BC, Galba betrayed the Lusitani leaders he had invited to peace talks and had them killed, ingloriously ending the first phase of the war.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Lusitani revolted again in 146 BC under a new leader called Viriathus, invading Turdetania (southern Iberia) in a guerrilla war.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Lusitanians were initially successful, defeating a Roman army at the Battle of Tribola and going on to sack nearby Carpetania, and then besting a second Roman army at the First Battle of Mount Venus in 146 BC, again going on to sack another nearby city.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 144 BC, the general Quintus Fabius Maximus Aemilianus campaigned successfully against the Lusitani, but failed in his attempts to arrest Viriathus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 144 BC, Viriathus formed a league against Rome with several Celtiberian tribes and persuaded them to rise against Rome too, in the Second Numantine War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Viriathus' new coalition bested Roman armies at the Second Battle of Mount Venus in 144 BC and again at the failed Siege of Erisone.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 139 BC, Viriathus was finally killed in his sleep by three of his companions who had been promised gifts by Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 136 and 135 BC, more attempts were made to gain complete control of the region of Numantia, but they failed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 134 BC, the Consul Scipio Aemilianus finally succeeded in suppressing the rebellion following the successful Siege of Numantia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Since the Roman invasion of the Iberian Peninsula had begun in the south in the territories around the Mediterranean controlled by the Barcids, the last region of the peninsula to be subdued lay in the far north.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Cantabrian Wars or Astur-Cantabrian Wars, from 29 BC to 19 BC, occurred during the Roman conquest of these northern provinces of Cantabria and Asturias.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome's preoccupation with its war with Carthage provided an opportunity for Philip V of the kingdom of Macedon in northern Greece to attempt to extend his power westward.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Philip sent ambassadors to Hannibal's camp in Italy, to negotiate an alliance as common enemies of Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, Rome discovered the agreement when Philip's emissaries, along with emissaries from Hannibal, were captured by a Roman fleet.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The First Macedonian War saw the Romans involved directly in only limited land operations.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] When the Aetolians sued for peace with Philip, Rome's small expeditionary force, with no more allies in Greece, was ready to make peace.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome had achieved its objective of pre-occupying Philip and preventing him from aiding Hannibal.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] A treaty was drawn up between Rome and Macedon at Phoenice in 205 BC which promised Rome a small indemnity, formally ending the First Macedonian War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Macedon began to encroach on territory claimed by several other Greek city states in 200 BC and these pleaded for help from their newfound ally Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome gave Philip an ultimatum that he must submit Macedonia to being essentially a Roman province.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Philip, unsurprisingly, refused and, after initial internal reluctance for further hostilities, Rome declared war against Philip in the Second Macedonian War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the Battle of the Aous Roman forces under Titus Quinctius Flamininus defeated the Macedonians, and in a second larger battle under the same opposing commanders in 197 BC, in the Battle of Cynoscephalae, Flamininus again beat the Macedonians decisively.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Macedonia was forced to sign the Treaty of Tempea, in which it lost all claim to territory in Greece and Asia, and had to pay a war indemnity to Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Between the second and third Macedonian wars Rome faced further conflict in the region due to a tapestry of shifting rivalries, alliances and leagues all seeking to gain greater influence.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After the Macedonians had been defeated in the Second Macedonian War in 197 BC, the Greek city-state of Sparta stepped into the partial power vacuum in Greece.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Fearing the Spartans would take increasing control of the region, the Romans drew on help from allies to prosecute the Roman-Spartan War, defeating a Spartan army at the Battle of Gythium in 195 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] They also fought their former allies the Aetolian League in the Aetolian War, against the Istrians in the Istrian War, against the Illyrians in the Illyrian War, and against Achaia in the Achaean War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome now turned its attentions to Antiochus III of the Seleucid Empire to the east.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After campaigns as far abroad as Bactria, India, Persia and Judea, Antiochus moved to Asia Minor and Thrace to secure several coastal towns, a move that brought him into conflict with Roman interests.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 179 BC Philip died and his talented and ambitious son, Perseus of Macedon, took his throne and showed a renewed interest in Greece.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] He also allied himself with the warlike Bastarnae, and both this and his actions in Greece possibly violated the treaty signed with the Romans by his father or, if not, certainly was not "behaving as [Rome considered] a subordinate ally should".
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome declared war on Macedonia again, starting the Third Macedonian War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Perseus initially had greater military success against the Romans than his father, winning the Battle of Callicinus against a Roman consular army.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, as with all such ventures in this period, Rome responded by simply sending another army.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The second consular army duly defeated the Macedonians at the Battle of Pydna in 168 BC and the Macedonians, lacking the reserve of the Romans and with King Perseus captured, duly capitulated, ending the Third Macedonian War.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Fourth Macedonian War, fought from 150 BC to 148 BC, was the final war between Rome and Macedon and began when Andriscus usurped the Macedonian throne.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Romans raised a consular army under Quintus Caecilius Metellus, who swiftly defeated Andriscus at the Second battle of Pydna.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Under Lucius Mummius, Corinth was destroyed following a siege in 146 BC, leading to the surrender and thus conquest of the Achaean League (see Battle of Corinth).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome had, in the earlier Punic Wars, gained large tracts of territory in Africa, which they consolidated in the following centuries.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Much of that land had been granted to the kingdom of Numidia, a kingdom on the north African coast approximating to modern Algeria, in return for its past military assistance.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Jugurthine War of 111–104 BC was fought between Rome and Jugurtha of Numidia and constituted the final Roman pacification of Northern Africa, after which Rome largely ceased expansion on the continent after reaching natural barriers of desert and mountain.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In response to Jugurtha's usurpation of the Numidian throne, a loyal ally of Rome since the Punic Wars, Rome intervened.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Jugurtha impudently bribed the Romans into accepting his usurpation and was granted half the kingdom.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Following further aggression and further bribery attempts, the Romans sent an army to depose him.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Romans were defeated at the Battle of Suthul but fared better at the Battle of the Muthul and finally defeated Jugurtha at the Battle of Thala, the Battle of Mulucha, and the Battle of Cirta (104 BC).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Jugurtha was finally captured not in battle but by treachery, ending the war.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Memories of the sack of Rome by Celtic tribes from Gaul in 390/387 BC, had been made into a legendary account that was taught to each generation of Roman youth, were still prominent despite their historical distance.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 121 BC, Rome came into contact with the Celtic tribes of the Allobroges and the Arverni, both of which they defeated with apparent ease in the First Battle of Avignon near the Rhone river and the Second Battle of Avignon, the same year.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Cimbrian War (113–101 BC) was a far more serious affair than the earlier clashes of 121 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Germanic tribes of the *Cimbri* and the *Teutons* or *Teutones* migrated from northern Europe into Rome's northern territories, where they clashed with Rome and her allies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Cimbrian War was the first time since the Second Punic War that Italia and Rome itself had been seriously threatened, and caused great fear in Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The opening action of the Cimbrian War, the Battle of Noreia in 112 BC, ended in defeat and near disaster for the Romans.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 105 BC the Romans were defeated at the Battle of Arausio and was the costliest Rome had suffered since the Battle of Cannae.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The extensive campaigning abroad by Rome, and the rewarding of soldiers with plunder from those campaigns, led to the trend of soldiers becoming increasingly loyal to their commanders rather than to the state, and a willingness to follow their generals in battle against the state.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome was plagued by several slave uprisings during this period, in part because in the past century vast tracts of land had been given to veterans who farmed by use of slaves and who came to greatly outnumber their Roman masters.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the last century BC, at least twelve civil wars and rebellions occurred.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] This pattern did not break until Octavian (later *Caesar Augustus*) ended it by becoming a successful challenger to the Senate's authority, and was made *princeps* (emperor).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Between 135 BC and 71 BC there were three Servile Wars against the Roman state; the third, and most serious, may have involved the revolution of 120,000 to 150,000 slaves.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Additionally, in 91 BC the Social War broke out between Rome and its former allies in Italy, collectively known as the *Socii*, over the grievance that they shared the risk of Rome's military campaigns, but not its rewards.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Despite defeats such as the Battle of Fucine Lake, Roman troops defeated the Italian militias in decisive engagements, notably the Battle of Asculum.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Although they lost militarily, the *Socii* achieved their objectives with the legal proclamations of the *Lex Julia* and *Lex Plautia Papiria*, which granted citizenship to more than 500,000 Italians.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The internal unrest reached its most serious stage in the two civil wars or marches upon Rome by the consul Lucius Cornelius Sulla at the beginning of 82 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the Battle of the Colline Gate at the very door of the city of Rome, a Roman army under Sulla bested an army of the Roman senate and its Samnite allies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Mithridates VI was the ruler of Pontus, a large kingdom in Asia Minor, from 120 to 63 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] He is remembered as one of Rome's most formidable and successful enemies who engaged three of the most prominent generals of the late Roman Republic: Sulla, Lucullus, and Pompey the Great.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In a pattern familiar from the Punic Wars, the Romans came into conflict with him after the two states' spheres of influence began to overlap.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Mithridates antagonised Rome by seeking to expand his kingdom, and Rome for her part seemed equally keen for war and the spoils and prestige that it might bring.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After conquering western Anatolia (modern Turkey) in 88 BC, Roman sources claim that Mithridates ordered the killing of the majority of the 80,000 Romans living there.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] A peace was made between Rome and Pontus, but this proved only a temporary lull.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Second Mithridatic War began when Rome tried to annex Bithynia as a province.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the Third Mithridatic War, first Lucius Licinius Lucullus and then Pompey the Great were sent against Mithridates.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Mithridates was finally defeated by Pompey in the night-time Battle of the Lycus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After defeating Mithridates, Pompey invaded Caucacus, subjugated the Kingdom of Iberia and established Roman control over Colchis.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The Mediterranean had at this time fallen into the hands of pirates, largely from Cilicia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Rome had destroyed many of the states that had previously policed the Mediterranean with fleets, but had failed to step into the gap created.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The pirates had seized the opportunity of a relative power vacuum and had not only strangled shipping lanes but had plundered many cities on the coasts of Greece and Asia, and had even made descents upon Italy itself.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After the Roman admiral Marcus Antonius Creticus (father of the triumvir Marcus Antonius) failed to clear the pirates to the satisfaction of the Roman authorities, Pompey was nominated his successor as commander of a special naval task force to campaign against them.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] It supposedly took Pompey just forty days to clear the western portion of the western Mediterranean of pirates, and restore communication between Iberia, Africa, and Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Plutarch describes how Pompey first swept their craft from the Mediterranean in a series of small actions and through the promise of honouring the surrender of cities and craft.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] He then followed the main body of the pirates to their strongholds on the coast of Cilicia, and destroyed them there in the naval Battle of Korakesion.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] During a term as praetor in Iberia, Pompey's contemporary Julius Caesar of the Roman Julii clan defeated the Calaici and Lusitani in battle.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Following a consular term, he was then appointed to a five-year term as Proconsular Governor of Transalpine Gaul (current southern France) and Illyria (the coast of Dalmatia).
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Not content with an idle governorship, Caesar strove to find reason to invade Gaul, which would give him the dramatic military success he sought.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] To this end he stirred up popular nightmares of the first sack of Rome by the Gauls and the more recent spectre of the Cimbri and Teutones.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] When the Helvetii and Tigurini tribes began to migrate on a route that would take them near (not into) the Roman province of Transalpine Gaul, Caesar had the barely sufficient excuse he needed for his Gallic Wars, fought between 58 BC and 49 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After slaughtering the Helvetii tribe, Caesar prosecuted a "long, bitter and costly" campaign against other tribes across the breadth of Gaul, many of whom had fought alongside Rome against their common enemy the Helvetii, and annexed their territory to that of Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Plutarch claims that the campaign cost a million Gallic lives.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Although "fierce and able" the Gauls were handicapped by internal disunity and fell in a series of battles over the course of a decade.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 55 and 54 BC he made two expeditions to Britain.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 52 BC, following the Siege of Avaricum and a string of inconclusive battles, Caesar defeated a union of Gauls led by Vercingetorix at the Battle of Alesia, completing the Roman conquest of Transalpine Gaul.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By 50 BC, the entirety of Gaul lay in Roman hands.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Caesar recorded his own accounts of these campaigns in *Commentarii de Bello Gallico* ("Commentaries on the Gallic War").
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Gaul never regained its Celtic identity, never attempted another nationalist rebellion, and remained loyal to Rome until the fall of the Western Empire in 476 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] By 59 BC an unofficial political alliance known as the First Triumvirate was formed between Gaius Julius Caesar, Marcus Licinius Crassus, and Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus to share power and influence.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] It was always an uncomfortable alliance given that Crassus and Pompey intensely disliked one another.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 53 BC, Crassus launched a Roman invasion of the Parthian Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] After initial successes, he marched his army deep into the desert; but here his army was cut off deep in enemy territory, surrounded and slaughtered at the Battle of Carrhae in "the greatest Roman defeat since Hannibal" in which Crassus himself perished.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The death of Crassus removed some of the balance in the Triumvirate and, consequently, Caesar and Pompey began to move apart.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] While Caesar was fighting against Vercingetorix in Gaul, Pompey proceeded with a legislative agenda for Rome that revealed that he was at best ambivalent towards Caesar and perhaps now covertly allied with Caesar's political enemies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 51 BC, some Roman senators demanded that Caesar would not be permitted to stand for Consul unless he turned over control of his armies to the state, and the same demands were made of Pompey by other factions.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Relinquishing his army would leave Caesar defenceless before his enemies.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Caesar chose Civil War over laying down his command and facing trial.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The triumvirate was shattered and conflict was inevitable.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Pompey initially assured Rome and the senate that he could defeat Caesar in battle should he march on Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, by the spring of 49 BC, when Caesar crossed the Rubicon river with his invading forces and swept down the Italian peninsula towards Rome, Pompey ordered the abandonment of Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Caesar's army was still under-strength, with certain units remaining in Gaul, but on the other hand Pompey himself only had a small force at his command, and that with uncertain loyalty having served under Caesar.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Tom Holland attributes Pompey's willingness to abandon Rome to waves of panicking refugees as an attempt to stir ancestral fears of invasions from the north.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Pompey's forces retreated south towards Brundisium, and then fled to Greece.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Caesar first directed his attention to the Pompeian stronghold of Iberia but following campaigning by Caesar in the Siege of Massilia and Battle of Ilerda he decided to attack Pompey in Greece.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Pompey initially defeated Caesar at the Battle of Dyrrachium in 48 BC but failed to follow up on the victory.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Pompey was decisively defeated in the Battle of Pharsalus in 48 BC despite outnumbering Caesar's forces two to one.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Pompey fled again, this time to Egypt, where he was murdered in an attempt to ingratiate the country with Caesar and avoid a war with Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Pompey's death did not see the end of the civil wars since initially Caesar's enemies were manifold and Pompey's supporters continued to fight on after his death.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 46 BC Caesar lost perhaps as much as a third of his army when his former commander Titus Labienus, who had defected to the Pompeians several years earlier, defeated him at the Battle of Ruspina.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] However, after this low point Caesar came back to defeat the Pompeian army of Metellus Scipio in the Battle of Thapsus, after which the Pompeians retreated yet again to Iberia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Caesar defeated the combined forces of Titus Labienus and Gnaeus Pompey the Younger at the Battle of Munda in Iberia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Labienus was killed in the battle and the Younger Pompey captured and executed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Despite his military success, or probably because of it, fear spread of Caesar, now the primary figure of the Roman state, becoming an autocratic ruler and ending the Roman Republic.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] This fear drove a group of senators naming themselves The Liberators to assassinate him in 44 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Further civil war followed between those loyal to Caesar and those who supported the actions of the Liberators.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Caesar's supporter Mark Antony condemned Caesar's assassins and war broke out between the two factions.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Antony was denounced as a public enemy, and Octavian was entrusted with the command of the war against him.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In the Battle of Forum Gallorum Antony, besieging Caesar's assassin Decimus Brutus in Mutina, defeated the forces of the consul Pansa, who was killed, but Antony was then immediately defeated by the army of the other consul, Hirtius.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] At the Battle of Mutina Antony was again defeated in battle by Hirtius, who was killed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Although Antony failed to capture Mutina, Decimus Brutus was murdered shortly thereafter.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Octavian betrayed his party, and came to terms with Caesarians Antony and Lepidus and on 26 November 43 BC the Second Triumvirate was formed, this time in an official capacity.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] In 42 BC Triumvirs Mark Antony and Octavian fought the indecisive Battle of Philippi with Caesar's assassins Marcus Brutus and Cassius.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Although Brutus defeated Octavian, Antony defeated Cassius, who committed suicide.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Brutus also committed suicide shortly afterwards.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Civil war flared again when the Second Triumvirate of Octavian, Lepidus and Mark Antony failed just as the first had almost as soon as its opponents had been removed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The ambitious Octavian built a power base and then launched a campaign against Mark Antony.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Together with Lucius Antonius, Mark Antony's wife Fulvia raised an army in Italy to fight for Antony's rights against Octavian but she was defeated by Octavian at the Battle of Perugia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Her death led to partial reconciliation between Octavian and Antony who went on to crush the army of Sextus Pompeius, the last focus of opposition to the second triumvirate, in the naval Battle of Naulochus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] As before, once opposition to the triumvirate was crushed, it started to tear at itself.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] The triumvirate expired on the last day of 33 BC and was not renewed in law and in 31 BC, war began again.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] At the Battle of Actium, Octavian decisively defeated Antony and Cleopatra in a naval battle near Greece, using fire to destroy the enemy fleet.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p02] Octavian went on to become Emperor under the name Augustus and, in the absence of political assassins or usurpers, was able to greatly expand the borders of the Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Secured from internal threats, Rome achieved great territorial gains in both the East and the West.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In the West, following humiliating defeats at the hands of the Sugambri, Tencteri and Usipetes tribes in 16 BC, Roman armies pushed north and east out of Gaul to subdue much of Germania.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Pannonian revolt in 6 AD forced the Romans to cancel their plan to cement their conquest of Germania.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Despite the loss of a large army almost to the man of Varus' famous defeat at the hands of the Germanic leader Arminius in the Battle of the Teutoburg Forest in 9 AD, Rome recovered and continued its expansion up to and beyond the borders of the known world.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Roman armies under Germanicus pursued several more campaigns against the Germanic tribes of the Marcomanni, Hermunduri, Chatti, Cherusci, Bructeri, and Marsi.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Overcoming several mutinies in the armies along the Rhine, Germanicus defeated the Germanic tribes of Arminius in a series of battles culminating in the Battle of the Weser River.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After Caesar's preliminary low-scale invasions of Britain, the Romans invaded in force in 43 AD, forcing their way inland through several battles against British tribes, including the Battle of the Medway, the Battle of the Thames, the Battle of Caer Caradoc and the Battle of Mona.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Following a general uprising in which the Britons sacked Colchester, St Albans and London, the Romans suppressed the rebellion in the Battle of Watling Street and went on to push as far north as central Scotland in the Battle of Mons Graupius.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Tribes in modern-day Scotland and Northern England repeatedly rebelled against Roman rule and two military bases were established in Britannia to protect against rebellion and incursions from the north, from which Roman troops built and manned Hadrian's Wall.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] On the continent, the extension of the Empire's borders beyond the Rhine hung in the balance for some time, with the emperor Caligula apparently poised to invade Germania in 39 AD, and Cnaeus Domitius Corbulo crossing the Rhine in 47 AD and marching into the territory of the Frisii and Chauci.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Caligula's successor, Claudius, ordered the suspension of further attacks across the Rhine, setting what was to become the permanent limit of the Empire's expansion in this direction.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Further east, Trajan turned his attention to Dacia, an area north of Macedon and Greece and east of the Danube that had been on the Roman agenda since before the days of Caesar when they had beaten a Roman army at the Battle of Histria.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 85 AD, the Dacians had swarmed over the Danube and pillaged Moesia and initially defeated an army the Emperor Domitian sent against them, but the Romans were victorious in the Battle of Tapae in AD 88 and a truce was drawn up.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Emperor Trajan recommenced hostilities against Dacia and, following an uncertain number of battles, defeated the Dacian general Decebalus in the Second Battle of Tapae in 101 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] With Trajan's troops pressing towards the Dacian capital Sarmizegethusa, Decebalus once more sought terms.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Decebalus rebuilt his power over the following years and attacked Roman garrisons again in 105 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In response Trajan again marched into Dacia, besieging the Dacian capital in the Siege of Sarmizegethusa, and razing it to the ground.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] With Dacia quelled, Trajan subsequently invaded the Parthian empire to the east, his conquests taking the Roman Empire to its greatest extent.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Rome's borders in the east were indirectly governed through a system of client states for some time, leading to less direct campaigning than in the west in this period.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Kingdom of Armenia between the Black Sea and Caspian Sea became a focus of contention between Rome and the Parthian Empire, and control of the region was repeatedly gained and lost.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Parthians forced Armenia into submission from 37 AD but in 47 AD the Romans retook control of the kingdom and offered it client kingdom status.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Under Nero, the Romans fought a campaign between 55 and 63 AD against the Parthian Empire, which had again invaded Armenia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After gaining Armenia once more in 60 AD and subsequently losing it again in 62 AD, the Romans sent Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo in 63 AD into the territories of Vologases I of Parthia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Corbulo succeeded in returning Armenia to Roman client status, where it remained for the next century.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 69 AD, Marcus Salvius Otho, governor of Lusitania, had the Emperor Galba murdered and claimed the throne for himself.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, Vitellius, governor of the province of Germania Inferior, had also claimed the throne and marched on Rome with his troops.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Following an inconclusive battle near Antipolis, Vitellius' troops attacked the city of Placentia in the Assault of Placentia, but were repulsed by the Othonian garrison.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Otho left Rome on March 14, and marched north towards Placentia to meet his challenger.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In the Battle of Locus Castorum the Othonians had the better of the fighting, and Vitellius' troops retreated to Cremona.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The two armies met again on the Via Postunia, in the First Battle of Bedriacum, after which the Othonian troops fled back to their camp in Bedriacum, and the next day surrendered to the Vitellian forces.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Otho decided to commit suicide rather than fight on.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Meanwhile, the forces stationed in the Middle East provinces of Judaea and Syria had acclaimed Vespasian as emperor and the Danubian armies of the provinces of Raetia and Moesia also acclaimed Vespasian as emperor.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Vespasian's and Vitellius' armies met in the Second Battle of Bedriacum, after which the Vitellian troops were driven back into their camp outside Cremona, which was taken.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Vespasian's troops then attacked Cremona itself, which surrendered.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Under pretence of siding with Vespasian, Civilis of Batavia had taken up arms and induced the inhabitants of his native country to rebel.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The rebelling Batavians were immediately joined by several neighbouring German tribes including the Frisii.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] These forces drove out the Roman garrisons near the Rhine and defeated a Roman army at the Battle of Castra Vetera, after which many Roman troops along the Rhine and in Gaul defected to the Batavian cause.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, disputes soon broke out amongst the different tribes, rendering co-operation impossible; Vespasian, having successfully ended the civil war, called upon Civilis to lay down his arms, and on his refusal his legions met him in force, defeating him in the Battle of Augusta Treverorum.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The First Jewish-Roman War, sometimes called The Great Revolt, was the first of three major rebellions by the Jews of Judaea against the Roman Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] According to Fergus Millar, the revolt represents "the best-attested series of operations by the Roman army in the entire history of the Empire." Judaea, an independent kingdom under the Hasmoneans, fell into a civil war in which Pompey intervened, conquering Jerusalem in 63 BC.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The territory gradually transformed into a client kingdom before eventually becoming a directly governed province.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Jewish anger towards Rome grew due to the incompetent and often harsh rule of successive governors coupled with Roman insensitivity – Tacitus says disgust and repulsion – towards their religion.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] This discontent was further fueled by ethnic tensions between Jews and pagans, economic and social issues, and aspirations for national independence.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The spark came in 66 AD, when violence broke out in Jerusalem after the Roman governor seized a large amount of money from the Temple and killed many; this act led to an open uprising against Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Cestius Gallus, the Roman governor of Syria, attempted to quell the revolt but withdrew after initial engagements in Jerusalem, with his force decisively ambushed and annihilated in the Battle of Beth-Horon, losing a contingent equivalent to a legion.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By this point, the revolt attracted greater attention from Rome and Emperor Nero appointed general Vespasian to crush the rebellion.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Vespasian led his forces in a methodical clearance of the areas in revolt.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By the year 68 AD, Jewish resistance in the Galilee had been crushed, with the Romans besieging and destroying rebel strongholds such as Yodfat and Gamla.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 70 AD, Titus succeeded Vespasian and, using a force significantly larger than the one deployed for the Roman invasion of Britain, managed to take Jerusalem after a long siege, during which the Temple was razed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The city was systematically destroyed, with much of its population massacred or enslaved.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Roman forces continued to suppress remaining resistance, culminating in the Siege of Masada in 73 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Flavian dynasty leveraged the victory to solidify its claim to imperial rule.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] This was achieved through a triumph in Rome (the only one celebrating the subjugation of an existing province's population), the minting of Judaea Capta coins, and the construction of commemorative monuments such as the Arch of Titus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Circa 115 AD, a series of revolts broke out among Jewish diaspora communities in the eastern provinces of the Roman Empire while Trajan was engaged in his Parthian campaign.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The revolts, which came to be known as the Diaspora Revolt, erupted nearly simultaneously in Egypt, Libya, and Cyprus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Marcius Turbo, a leading general, was sent to quell the uprisings in Egypt and Libya, while Lusius Quietus handled Jewish unrest in Mesopotamia and Judaea (the "Kitos War").
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The uprisings were largely suppressed by late 117 AD, just before Trajan's death, resulting in the annihilation and expulsion of Jewish communities in Egypt, Libya, and Cyprus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 132 AD, the Bar Kokhba revolt emerged as the final major Jewish uprising against Roman authority and the last bid for Jewish independence in Judaea.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The immediate triggers of the revolt, still debated by scholars, include Hadrian's establishment of the pagan colony Aelia Capitolina on the ruins of Jerusalem and his prohibition of circumcision.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Led by Simon bar Kokhba, the Jews initially succeeded in creating a brief independent state.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, the Romans assembled six full legions with auxiliaries and other elements from up to six additional legions, all under the command of Sextus Julius Severus, that effectively crushed the revolt by 135 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] This suppression caused extensive devastation across Judaea, leading to massive loss of life, widespread displacement, and enslavement, while also inflicting heavy casualties on Roman forces.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After the revolt, the province was renamed Syria Palaestina, and Jews were subjected to harsh religious restrictions.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By the 2nd century AD the territories of Persia were controlled by the Arsacid dynasty and known as the Parthian Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Due in large part to their employment of powerful heavy cavalry and mobile horse archers, Parthia was the most formidable enemy of the Roman Empire in the east.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] As early as 53 BC, the Roman general Crassus had invaded Parthia, but he was killed and his army was defeated at the Battle of Carrhae.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In the years following Carrhae, the Romans were divided in civil war and hence unable to campaign against Parthia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Trajan also campaigned against the Parthians from 114 to 117 AD and briefly captured their capital Ctesiphon, putting the puppet ruler Parthamaspates on the throne.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, rebellions in Babylonia and the Jewish revolts in Judaea made it difficult to maintain the captured province and the territories were abandoned.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] A revitalised Parthian Empire renewed its assault in 161 AD, defeating two Roman armies and invading Armenia and Syria.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Emperor Lucius Verus and general Gaius Avidius Cassius were sent in 162 AD to counter the resurgent Parthia.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In this war, the Parthian city of Seleucia on the Tigris was destroyed and the palace at the capital Ctesiphon was burned to the ground by Avidius Cassius in 164 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Parthians made peace but were forced to cede western Mesopotamia to the Romans.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 197 AD, Emperor Septimius Severus waged a brief and successful war against the Parthian Empire in retaliation for the support given to a rival for the imperial throne Pescennius Niger.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Parthian capital Ctesiphon was sacked by the Roman army, and the northern half of Mesopotamia was restored to Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Emperor Caracalla, the son of Severus, marched on Parthia in 217 AD from Edessa to begin a war against them, but he was assassinated while on the march.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 224 AD, the Parthian Empire was crushed not by the Romans but by the rebellious Persian vassal king Ardashir I, who revolted, leading to the establishment of Sassanid Empire of Persia, which replaced Parthia as Rome's major rival in the East.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After Varus' defeat in Germania in the 1st century, Rome had adopted a largely defensive strategy along the border with Germania, constructing a line of defences known as *limes* along the Rhine.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Cherusci, Bructeri, Tencteri, Usipi, Marsi, and Chatti of Varus' time had by the 3rd century either evolved into or been displaced by a confederacy or alliance of Germanic tribes collectively known as the Alamanni, first mentioned by Cassius Dio describing the campaign of Caracalla in 213 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In around 166 AD, several Germanic tribes pushed across the Danube, striking as far as Italy itself in the Siege of Aquileia in 166 AD, and the heartland of Greece in the Sack of Eleusis.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Carpi and Sarmatians whom Rome had held at bay were replaced by the Goths and likewise the Quadi and Marcomanni that Rome had defeated were replaced by the greater confederation of the Alamanni.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, their first major assault deep into Roman territory came in 268 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In that year the Romans were forced to denude much of their German frontier of troops in response to a massive invasion by another new Germanic tribal confederacy, the Goths, from the east.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The pressure of tribal groups pushing into the Empire was the result of a chain of migrations with its roots far to the east: Huns from the Russian steppe attacked the Goths, who in turn attacked the Dacians, Alans and Sarmatians at or within Rome's borders.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Goths first appeared in history as a distinct people in this invasion of 268 AD when they swarmed over the Balkan peninsula and overran the Roman provinces of Pannonia and Illyricum and even threatened Italia itself.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Alamanni seized the opportunity to launch a major invasion of Gaul and northern Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, the Visigoths were defeated in battle that summer near the modern Italian-Slovenian border and then routed in the Battle of Naissus that September by Gallienus, Claudius and Aurelian, who then turned and defeated the Alemanni at the Battle of Lake Benacus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Claudius' successor Aurelian defeated the Goths twice more in the Battle of Fanum Fortunae and the Battle of Ticinum.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Goths remained a major threat to the Empire but directed their attacks away from Italy itself for several years after their defeat.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By 284 AD, Gothic troops were serving on behalf of the Roman military as federated troops.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Alamanni on the other hand resumed their drive towards Italy almost immediately.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] They defeated Aurelian at the Battle of Placentia in 271 AD but were beaten back for a short time after they lost the battles of Fano and Pavia later that year.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] They were beaten again in 298 AD at the battles of Lingones and Vindonissa but fifty years later they were resurgent again, making incursions in 356 AD at the Battle of Reims, in 357 AD at the Battle of Strasbourg, in 367 AD at the Battle of Solicinium and in 378 AD at Battle of Argentovaria.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In the same year the Goths inflicted a crushing defeat on the Eastern Empire at the Battle of Adrianople, in which the Eastern Emperor Valens was massacred along with tens of thousands of Roman troops.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] At the same time, Franks raided through the North Sea and the English Channel, Vandals pressed across the Rhine, Iuthungi against the Danube, Iazyges, Carpi and Taifali harassed Dacia, and Gepids joined the Goths and Heruli in attacks round the Black Sea.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] At around the same time, lesser-known tribes such as the Bavares, Baquates and Quinquegentanei raided Africa.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] At the start of the 5th century, the pressure on Rome's western borders was growing intense.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, it was not only the western borders that were under threat: Rome was also under threat both internally and on its eastern borders.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] An army that was often willing to support its general over its emperor, meant that if commanders could establish sole control of their army, they could usurp the imperial throne from that position.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The so-called Crisis of the Third Century describes the turmoil of murder, usurpation and in-fighting that followed the murder of the Emperor Alexander Severus in 235 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, Cassius Dio marks the wider imperial decline as beginning in 180 AD with the ascension of Commodus to the throne, a judgement with which Gibbon concurred, and Matyszak states that "the rot ... had become established long before" even that.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Although the crisis of the 3rd century was not the absolute beginning of Rome's decline, it nevertheless did impose a severe strain on the empire as Romans waged war on one another as they had not done since the last days of the Republic.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Within the space of a single century, twenty-seven military officers declared themselves emperors and reigned over parts of the empire for months or days, all but two meeting with a violent end.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The time was characterized by a Roman army that was as likely to be attacking itself as it was an outside invader, reaching a low point around 258 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Ironically, while it was these usurpations that led to the breakup of the Empire during the crisis, it was the strength of several frontier generals that helped reunify the empire through force of arms.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The situation was complex, often with three or more usurpers in existence at once.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Septimius Severus and Pescennius Niger, both rebel generals declared to be emperors by the troops they commanded, clashed for the first time in 193 AD at the Battle of Cyzicus, in which Niger was defeated.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, it took two further defeats at the Battle of Nicaea later that year and the Battle of Issus the following year, for Niger to be destroyed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Almost as soon as Niger's usurpation had been ended, Severus was forced to deal with another rival for the throne in the person of Clodius Albinus, who had originally been allied to Severus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Albinus was proclaimed emperor by his troops in Britain and, crossing over to Gaul, defeated Severus' general Virius Lupus in battle, before being in turn defeated and killed in the Battle of Lugdunum by Severus himself.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After this turmoil, Severus faced no more internal threats for the rest of his reign, and the reign of his successor Caracalla passed uninterrupted for a while until he was murdered by Macrinus, who proclaimed himself emperor.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Despite Macrinus having his position ratified by the Roman senate, the troops of Varius Avitus declared him to be emperor instead, and the two met in battle at the Battle of Antioch in 218 AD, in which Macrinus was defeated.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, Avitus himself, after taking the imperial name Elagabalus, was murdered shortly afterwards and Alexander Severus was proclaimed emperor by both the Praetorian Guard and the senate who, after a short reign, was murdered in turn.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] His murderers were working on behalf of the army who were unhappy with their lot under his rule and who raised in his place Maximinus Thrax.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Gordian III's fate is not certain, although he may have been murdered by his own successor, Philip the Arab, who ruled for only a few years before the army again raised a general, Decius, by their proclamation to emperor, who then defeated Philip in the Battle of Verona.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Several succeeding generals avoided battling usurpers for the throne by being murdered by their own troops before battle could commence.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The lone exception to this rule was Gallienus, emperor from 260 to 268 AD, who confronted a remarkable array of usurpers, most of whom he defeated in pitched battle.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The army was mostly spared further infighting until around 273 AD, when Aurelian defeated the Gallic usurper Tetricus in the Battle of Chalons.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The next decade saw an incredible number of usurpers, sometimes three at the same time, all vying for the imperial throne.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Most of the battles are not recorded, due primarily to the turmoil of the time, until Diocletian, a usurper himself, defeated Carinus at the Battle of the Margus and became emperor.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Some small measure of stability again returned at this point, with the empire split into a Tetrarchy of two greater and two lesser emperors, a system that staved off civil wars for a short time until 312 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In that year, relations between the tetrarchy collapsed for good and Constantine I, Licinius, Maxentius and Maximinus jostled for control of the empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In the Battle of Turin Constantine defeated Maxentius, and in the Battle of Tzirallum, Licinius defeated Maximinus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] From 314 AD onwards, Constantine defeated Licinius in the Battle of Cibalae, then the Battle of Mardia, and then again at the Battle of Adrianople, the Battle of the Hellespont and the Battle of Chrysopolis.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Constantine then turned upon Maxentius, beating him in the Battle of Verona and the Battle of Milvian Bridge in the same year.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Constantine's son Constantius II inherited his father's rule and later defeated the usurper Magnentius in first the Battle of Mursa Major and then the Battle of Mons Seleucus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Successive emperors Valens and Theodosius I also defeated usurpers in, respectively, the Battle of Thyatira, and the battles of the Save and the Frigidus.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After overthrowing the Parthian confederacy, the Sassanid Empire that arose from its remains pursued a more aggressive expansionist policy than their predecessors and continued to make war against Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 230 AD, the first Sassanid emperor attacked Roman territory first in Armenia and then in Mesopotamia but Roman losses were largely restored by Severus within a few years.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Romans recovered Antioch by 253 AD, and Emperor Valerian gathered an army and marched eastward to the Sassanid borders.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 260 AD at the Battle of Edessa the Sassanids defeated the Roman army and captured the Roman Emperor Valerian.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By the late 3rd century, Roman fortunes on the eastern frontier improved dramatically.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] During a period of civil upheaval in Persia, emperor Carus led a successful campaign into Persia essentially uncontested, sacking Ctesiphon in 283 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] During the reign of the Tetrarchy, emperors Diocletian and Galerius brought a decisive conclusion to the war, sacking Ctesiphon in 299 AD and expanding the Roman eastern frontier dramatically with the Treaty of Nisibis.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The treaty brought lasting peace between Rome and the Sassanids for almost four decades until the end of Constantine the Great's reign.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 337 AD, Shapur II broke the peace and began a 26-year conflict, attempting with little success to conquer Roman fortresses in the region.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After early Sassanid successes including the Battle of Amida in 359 AD and the Siege of Pirisabora in 363 AD, Emperor Julian met Shapur in 363 AD in the Battle of Ctesiphon outside the walls of the Persian capital.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Romans were victorious but were unable to take the city, and were forced to retreat due to their vulnerable position in the middle of hostile territory.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Julian was killed in the Battle of Samarra during the retreat, possibly by one of his own men.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] There were several future wars, although all brief and small-scale, since both the Romans and the Sassanids were forced to deal with threats from other directions during the 5th century.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] A war against Bahram V in 420 AD over the persecution of the Christians in Persia led to a brief war that was soon concluded by treaty and in 441 AD a war with Yazdegerd II was again swiftly concluded by treaty after both parties battled threats elsewhere.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Many theories have been advanced in way of explanation for decline of the Roman Empire, and many dates given for its fall, from the onset of its decline in the 3rd century to the fall of Constantinople in 1453.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Militarily, however, the Empire finally fell after first being overrun by various non-Roman peoples and then having its heart in Italy seized by Germanic troops in a revolt.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The historicity and exact dates are uncertain, and some historians do not consider that the Empire fell at this point.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Empire became gradually less Romanised and increasingly Germanic in nature: although the Empire buckled under Visigothic assault, the overthrow of the last Emperor Romulus Augustus was carried out by federated Germanic troops from within the Roman army rather than by foreign troops.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In this sense had Odoacer not renounced the title of Emperor and named himself "King of Italy" instead, the Empire might have continued in name.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Its identity, however, was no longer Roman – it was increasingly populated and governed by Germanic peoples long before 476 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Roman people were by the 5th century "bereft of their military ethos" and the Roman army itself a mere supplement to federated troops of Goths, Huns, Franks and others fighting on their behalf.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Rome's last gasp began when the Goths revolted around 395 AD.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Led by Alaric I, they attempted to seize Constantinople, but were rebuffed and instead plundered much of Thrace in northern Greece.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 402 AD they besieged Mediolanum, the capital of Roman Emperor Honorius, defended by Roman Gothic troops.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The arrival of the Roman Stilicho and his army forced Alaric to lift his siege and move his army towards Hasta (modern Asti) in western Italy, where Stilicho attacked it at the Battle of Pollentia, capturing Alaric's camp.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Stilicho offered to return the prisoners in exchange for the Visigoths returning to Illyricum but upon arriving at Verona, Alaric halted his retreat.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Stilicho again attacked at the Battle of Verona and again defeated Alaric, forcing him to withdraw from Italy.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 405 AD, the Gothic king Radagaisus started a war by invading Italy itself, but were defeated.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, in 406 AD an unprecedented number of tribes took advantage of the freezing of the Rhine to cross *en masse*: Vandals, Suevi, Alans and Burgundians swept across the Rhine and met little resistance in the Sack of Moguntiacum and the Sack of Treviri, completely overrunning Gaul.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Despite this grave danger, or perhaps because of it, the Roman army continued to be wracked by usurpation, in one of which Stilicho, Rome's foremost defender of the period, was put to death.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] It is in this climate that, despite his earlier setback, Alaric returned again in 410 AD and managed to sack Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Roman capital had by this time moved to the Italian city of Ravenna, but some historians view 410 AD as an alternative date for the true fall of the Roman Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Without possession of Rome or many of its former provinces, and increasingly Germanic in nature, the Roman Empire after 410 AD had little in common with the earlier Empire.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By 410 AD, Britain had been mostly denuded of Roman troops, and by 425 AD was no longer part of the Empire, and much of western Europe was beset "by all kinds of calamities and disasters", coming under barbarian kingdoms ruled by Vandals, Suebians, Visigoths and Burgundians.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The remainder of Rome's territory—if not its nature—was defended for several decades following 410 AD largely by Flavius Aëtius, who managed to play off each of Rome's barbarian invaders against one another.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 435 AD he led a Hunnic army against the Visigoths at the Battle of Arles, and again in 436 AD at the Battle of Narbonne.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] In 451 AD he led a combined army, including his former enemy the Visigoths, against the Huns at the Battle of the Catalaunian Plains, where Aëtius managed to halt the Hunnic onslaught.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] However, Concordia, Altinum, Mediolanum, Ticinum, and Patavium were sacked, and the Huns returned a year later.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] After brutally razing Aquileia, the Huns continued to move towards Rome.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] It was at this point that Pope Leo I managed to convince Attila to leave.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Carthage, the second largest city in the empire, was lost along with much of North Africa in 439 AD to the Vandals, and the fate of Rome seemed sealed.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] By 476 AD, what remained of the Empire was completely in the hands of federated Germanic troops and when they revolted, led by Odoacer and deposed the Emperor Romulus Augustus there was nobody to stop them.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] Odoacer happened to hold the part of the Empire around Italy and Rome but other parts of the Empire were ruled by Visigoths, Ostrogoths, Franks, Alans and others.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Empire in the West had fallen, and its remnant in Italy was no longer Roman in nature.
[src:siege-hook/campaign-history-of-the-roman-military-p03] The Eastern Roman Empire and the Goths continued to fight over Rome and the surrounding area for many years, though by this point Rome's importance was primarily symbolic.
[src:siege-hook/siege-hook] A **siege hook** is a weapon used to pull stones from a wall during a siege.
[src:siege-hook/siege-hook] The method used was to penetrate the protective wall with the hook and then retract it, pulling away some of the wall with it.
